cli/README.md
     1â†’# Command-line tool
     2â†’
     3â†’The `mdbook` command-line tool is used to create and build books.
     4â†’After you have [installed](../guide/installation.md) `mdbook`, you can run the `mdbook help` command in your terminal to view the available commands.
     5â†’
     6â†’This following sections provide in-depth information on the different commands available.
     7â†’
     8â†’* [`mdbook init <directory>`](init.md) --- Creates a new book with minimal boilerplate to start with.
     9â†’* [`mdbook build`](build.md) --- Renders the book.
    10â†’* [`mdbook watch`](watch.md) --- Rebuilds the book any time a source file changes.
    11â†’* [`mdbook serve`](serve.md) --- Runs a web server to view the book, and rebuilds on changes.
    12â†’* [`mdbook test`](test.md) --- Tests Rust code samples.
    13â†’* [`mdbook clean`](clean.md) --- Deletes the rendered output.
    14â†’* [`mdbook completions`](completions.md) --- Support for shell auto-completion.
cli/arg-watcher.md
     1â†’#### `--watcher`
     2â†’
     3â†’There are different backends used to determine when a file has changed.
     4â†’
     5â†’* `poll` (default) --- Checks for file modifications by scanning the filesystem every second.
     6â†’* `native` --- Uses the native operating system facilities to receive notifications when files change.
     7â†’  This can have less constant overhead, but may not be as reliable as the `poll` based watcher. See these issues for more information: [#383](https://github.com/rust-lang/mdBook/issues/383) [#1441](https://github.com/rust-lang/mdBook/issues/1441) [#1707](https://github.com/rust-lang/mdBook/issues/1707) [#2035](https://github.com/rust-lang/mdBook/issues/2035) [#2102](https://github.com/rust-lang/mdBook/issues/2102)
cli/build.md
     1â†’# The build command
     2â†’
     3â†’The build command is used to render your book:
     4â†’
     5â†’```bash
     6â†’mdbook build
     7â†’```
     8â†’
     9â†’It will try to parse your `SUMMARY.md` file to understand the structure of your
    10â†’book and fetch the corresponding files. Note that this will also create files
    11â†’mentioned in `SUMMARY.md` which are not yet present.
    12â†’
    13â†’The rendered output will maintain the same directory structure as the source for
    14â†’convenience. Large books will therefore remain structured when rendered.
    15â†’
    16â†’#### Specify a directory
    17â†’
    18â†’The `build` command can take a directory as an argument to use as the book's
    19â†’root instead of the current working directory.
    20â†’
    21â†’```bash
    22â†’mdbook build path/to/book
    23â†’```
    24â†’
    25â†’#### `--open`
    26â†’
    27â†’When you use the `--open` (`-o`) flag, mdbook will open the rendered book in
    28â†’your default web browser after building it.
    29â†’
    30â†’#### `--dest-dir`
    31â†’
    32â†’The `--dest-dir` (`-d`) option allows you to change the output directory for the
    33â†’book. Relative paths are interpreted relative to the current directory. If
    34â†’not specified it will default to the value of the `build.build-dir` key in
    35â†’`book.toml`, or to `./book`.
    36â†’
    37â†’-------------------
    38â†’
    39â†’***Note:*** *The build command copies all files (excluding files with `.md` extension) from the source directory
    40â†’into the build directory.*
cli/clean.md
     1â†’# The clean command
     2â†’
     3â†’The clean command is used to delete the generated book and any other build
     4â†’artifacts.
     5â†’
     6â†’```bash
     7â†’mdbook clean
     8â†’```
     9â†’
    10â†’#### Specify a directory
    11â†’
    12â†’The `clean` command can take a directory as an argument to use as the book's
    13â†’root instead of the current working directory.
    14â†’
    15â†’```bash
    16â†’mdbook clean path/to/book
    17â†’```
    18â†’
    19â†’#### `--dest-dir`
    20â†’
    21â†’The `--dest-dir` (`-d`) option allows you to override the book's output
    22â†’directory, which will be deleted by this command. Relative paths are interpreted
    23â†’relative to the current directory. If not specified it will default to the
    24â†’value of the `build.build-dir` key in `book.toml`, or to `./book`.
    25â†’
    26â†’```bash
    27â†’mdbook clean --dest-dir=path/to/book
    28â†’```
    29â†’
    30â†’`path/to/book` could be absolute or relative.
cli/completions.md
     1â†’# The completions command
     2â†’
     3â†’The completions command is used to generate auto-completions for some common shells.
     4â†’This means when you type `mdbook` in your shell, you can then press your shell's auto-complete key (usually the Tab key) and it may display what the valid options are, or finish partial input.
     5â†’
     6â†’The completions first need to be installed for your shell:
     7â†’
     8â†’```bash
     9â†’# bash
    10â†’mdbook completions bash > ~/.local/share/bash-completion/completions/mdbook
    11â†’# oh-my-zsh
    12â†’mdbook completions zsh > ~/.oh-my-zsh/completions/_mdbook
    13â†’autoload -U compinit && compinit
    14â†’```
    15â†’
    16â†’The command prints a completion script for the given shell.
    17â†’Run `mdbook completions --help` for a list of supported shells.
    18â†’
    19â†’Where to place the completions depend on which shell you are using and your operating system.
    20â†’Consult your shell's documentation for more information one where to place the script.
cli/init.md
     1â†’# The init command
     2â†’
     3â†’There is some minimal boilerplate that is the same for every new book. It's for
     4â†’this purpose that mdBook includes an `init` command.
     5â†’
     6â†’The `init` command is used like this:
     7â†’
     8â†’```bash
     9â†’mdbook init
    10â†’```
    11â†’
    12â†’When using the `init` command for the first time, a couple of files will be set
    13â†’up for you:
    14â†’```bash
    15â†’book-test/
    16â†’â”œâ”€â”€ book
    17â†’â””â”€â”€ src
    18â†’    â”œâ”€â”€ chapter_1.md
    19â†’    â””â”€â”€ SUMMARY.md
    20â†’```
    21â†’
    22â†’- The `src` directory is where you write your book in markdown. It contains all
    23â†’  the source files, configuration files, etc.
    24â†’
    25â†’- The `book` directory is where your book is rendered. All the output is ready
    26â†’  to be uploaded to a server to be seen by your audience.
    27â†’
    28â†’- The `SUMMARY.md` is the skeleton of your
    29â†’  book, and is discussed in more detail [in another
    30â†’  chapter](../format/summary.md).
    31â†’
    32â†’#### Tip: Generate chapters from SUMMARY.md
    33â†’
    34â†’When a `SUMMARY.md` file already exists, the `init` command will first parse it
    35â†’and generate the missing files according to the paths used in the `SUMMARY.md`.
    36â†’This allows you to think and create the whole structure of your book and then
    37â†’let mdBook generate it for you.
    38â†’
    39â†’#### Specify a directory
    40â†’
    41â†’The `init` command can take a directory as an argument to use as the book's root
    42â†’instead of the current working directory.
    43â†’
    44â†’```bash
    45â†’mdbook init path/to/book
    46â†’```
    47â†’
    48â†’#### `--theme`
    49â†’
    50â†’When you use the `--theme` flag, the default theme will be copied into a
    51â†’directory called `theme` in your source directory so that you can modify it.
    52â†’
    53â†’The theme is selectively overwritten, this means that if you don't want to
    54â†’overwrite a specific file, just delete it and the default file will be used.
    55â†’
    56â†’#### `--title`
    57â†’
    58â†’Specify a title for the book. If not supplied, an interactive prompt will ask for 
    59â†’a title. 
    60â†’
    61â†’```bash
    62â†’mdbook init --title="my amazing book"
    63â†’```
    64â†’
    65â†’#### `--ignore`
    66â†’
    67â†’Create a `.gitignore` file configured to ignore the `book` directory created when [building] a book. 
    68â†’If not supplied, an interactive prompt will ask whether it should be created.
    69â†’
    70â†’```bash
    71â†’mdbook init --ignore=none
    72â†’```
    73â†’
    74â†’```bash
    75â†’mdbook init --ignore=git
    76â†’```
    77â†’
    78â†’[building]: build.md
    79â†’
    80â†’#### `--force`
    81â†’
    82â†’Skip the prompts to create a `.gitignore` and for the title for the book.
cli/serve.md
     1â†’# The serve command
     2â†’
     3â†’The serve command is used to preview a book by serving it via HTTP at
     4â†’`localhost:3000` by default: 
     5â†’
     6â†’```bash
     7â†’mdbook serve
     8â†’```
     9â†’
    10â†’The `serve` command  watches the book's `src` directory for
    11â†’changes, rebuilding the book and refreshing clients for each change; this includes
    12â†’re-creating deleted files still mentioned in `SUMMARY.md`! A websocket
    13â†’connection is used to trigger the client-side refresh.
    14â†’
    15â†’***Note:*** *The `serve` command is for testing a book's HTML output, and is not
    16â†’intended to be a complete HTTP server for a website.*
    17â†’
    18â†’#### Specify a directory
    19â†’
    20â†’The `serve` command can take a directory as an argument to use as the book's
    21â†’root instead of the current working directory.
    22â†’
    23â†’```bash
    24â†’mdbook serve path/to/book
    25â†’```
    26â†’
    27â†’### Server options
    28â†’
    29â†’The `serve` hostname defaults to `localhost`, and the port defaults to `3000`. Either option can be specified on the command line:
    30â†’
    31â†’```bash
    32â†’mdbook serve path/to/book -p 8000 -n 127.0.0.1 
    33â†’```
    34â†’
    35â†’#### `--open`
    36â†’
    37â†’When you use the `--open` (`-o`) flag, mdbook will open the book in your
    38â†’default web browser after starting the server.
    39â†’
    40â†’#### `--dest-dir`
    41â†’
    42â†’The `--dest-dir` (`-d`) option allows you to change the output directory for the
    43â†’book. Relative paths are interpreted relative to the current directory. If
    44â†’not specified it will default to the value of the `build.build-dir` key in
    45â†’`book.toml`, or to `./book`.
    46â†’
    47â†’{{#include arg-watcher.md}}
    48â†’
    49â†’#### Specify exclude patterns
    50â†’
    51â†’The `serve` command will not automatically trigger a build for files listed in
    52â†’the `.gitignore` file in the book root directory. The `.gitignore` file may
    53â†’contain file patterns described in the [gitignore
    54â†’documentation](https://git-scm.com/docs/gitignore). This can be useful for
    55â†’ignoring temporary files created by some editors.
    56â†’
    57â†’***Note:*** *Only the `.gitignore` from the book root directory is used. Global
    58â†’`$HOME/.gitignore` or `.gitignore` files in parent directories are not used.*
cli/test.md
     1â†’# The test command
     2â†’
     3â†’When writing a book, you sometimes need to automate some tests. For example,
     4â†’[The Rust Programming Book](https://doc.rust-lang.org/stable/book/) uses a lot
     5â†’of code examples that could get outdated. Therefore it is very important for
     6â†’them to be able to automatically test these code examples.
     7â†’
     8â†’mdBook supports a `test` command that will run all available tests in a book. At
     9â†’the moment, only Rust tests are supported.
    10â†’
    11â†’#### Disable tests on a code block
    12â†’
    13â†’rustdoc doesn't test code blocks which contain the `ignore` attribute:
    14â†’
    15â†’    ```rust,ignore
    16â†’    fn main() {}
    17â†’    ```
    18â†’
    19â†’rustdoc also doesn't test code blocks which specify a language other than Rust:
    20â†’
    21â†’    ```markdown
    22â†’    **Foo**: _bar_
    23â†’    ```
    24â†’
    25â†’rustdoc *does* test code blocks which have no language specified:
    26â†’
    27â†’    ```
    28â†’    This is going to cause an error!
    29â†’    ```
    30â†’
    31â†’#### Specify a directory
    32â†’
    33â†’The `test` command can take a directory as an argument to use as the book's root
    34â†’instead of the current working directory.
    35â†’
    36â†’```bash
    37â†’mdbook test path/to/book
    38â†’```
    39â†’
    40â†’#### `--library-path`
    41â†’
    42â†’The `--library-path` (`-L`) option allows you to add directories to the library
    43â†’search path used by `rustdoc` when it builds and tests the examples. Multiple
    44â†’directories can be specified with multiple options (`-L foo -L bar`) or with a
    45â†’comma-delimited list (`-L foo,bar`). The path should point to the Cargo
    46â†’[build cache](https://doc.rust-lang.org/cargo/guide/build-cache.html) `deps` directory that
    47â†’contains the build output of your project. For example, if your Rust project's book is in a directory
    48â†’named `my-book`, the following command would include the crate's dependencies when running `test`:
    49â†’
    50â†’```shell
    51â†’mdbook test my-book -L target/debug/deps/
    52â†’```
    53â†’
    54â†’See the `rustdoc` command-line [documentation](https://doc.rust-lang.org/rustdoc/command-line-arguments.html#-l--library-path-where-to-look-for-dependencies)
    55â†’for more information.
    56â†’
    57â†’#### `--chapter`
    58â†’
    59â†’The `--chapter` (`-c`) option allows you to test a specific chapter of the
    60â†’book using the chapter name or the relative path to the chapter.
cli/watch.md
     1â†’# The watch command
     2â†’
     3â†’The `watch` command is useful when you want your book to be rendered on every
     4â†’file change. You could repeatedly issue `mdbook build` every time a file is
     5â†’changed. But using `mdbook watch` once will watch your files and will trigger a
     6â†’build automatically whenever you modify a file; this includes re-creating
     7â†’deleted files still mentioned in `SUMMARY.md`!
     8â†’
     9â†’#### Specify a directory
    10â†’
    11â†’The `watch` command can take a directory as an argument to use as the book's
    12â†’root instead of the current working directory.
    13â†’
    14â†’```bash
    15â†’mdbook watch path/to/book
    16â†’```
    17â†’
    18â†’#### `--open`
    19â†’
    20â†’When you use the `--open` (`-o`) option, mdbook will open the rendered book in
    21â†’your default web browser.
    22â†’
    23â†’#### `--dest-dir`
    24â†’
    25â†’The `--dest-dir` (`-d`) option allows you to change the output directory for the
    26â†’book. Relative paths are interpreted relative to the current directory. If
    27â†’not specified it will default to the value of the `build.build-dir` key in
    28â†’`book.toml`, or to `./book`.
    29â†’
    30â†’{{#include arg-watcher.md}}
    31â†’
    32â†’#### Specify exclude patterns
    33â†’
    34â†’The `watch` command will not automatically trigger a build for files listed in
    35â†’the `.gitignore` file in the book root directory. The `.gitignore` file may
    36â†’contain file patterns described in the [gitignore
    37â†’documentation](https://git-scm.com/docs/gitignore). This can be useful for
    38â†’ignoring temporary files created by some editors.
    39â†’
    40â†’_Note: Only `.gitignore` from book root directory is used. Global
    41â†’`$HOME/.gitignore` or `.gitignore` files in parent directories are not used._
continuous-integration.md
     1â†’# Running `mdbook` in continuous integration
     2â†’
     3â†’There are a variety of services such as [GitHub Actions] or [GitLab CI/CD] which can be used to test and deploy your book automatically.
     4â†’
     5â†’The following provides some general guidelines on how to configure your service to run mdBook.
     6â†’Specific recipes can be found at the [Automated Deployment] wiki page.
     7â†’
     8â†’[GitHub Actions]: https://docs.github.com/en/actions
     9â†’[GitLab CI/CD]: https://docs.gitlab.com/ee/ci/
    10â†’[Automated Deployment]: https://github.com/rust-lang/mdBook/wiki/Automated-Deployment
    11â†’
    12â†’## Installing mdBook
    13â†’
    14â†’There are several different strategies for installing mdBook.
    15â†’The particular method depends on your needs and preferences.
    16â†’
    17â†’### Pre-compiled binaries
    18â†’
    19â†’Perhaps the easiest method is to use the pre-compiled binaries found on the [GitHub Releases page][releases].
    20â†’A simple approach would be to use the popular `curl` CLI tool to download the executable:
    21â†’
    22â†’```sh
    23â†’mkdir bin
    24â†’curl -sSL https://github.com/rust-lang/mdBook/releases/download/{{ mdbook-version }}/mdbook-{{ mdbook-version }}-x86_64-unknown-linux-gnu.tar.gz | tar -xz --directory=bin
    25â†’bin/mdbook build
    26â†’```
    27â†’
    28â†’Some considerations for this approach:
    29â†’
    30â†’* This is relatively fast, and does not necessarily require dealing with caching.
    31â†’* This does not require installing Rust.
    32â†’* Specifying a specific URL means you have to manually update your script to get a new version.
    33â†’  This may be a benefit if you want to lock to a specific version.
    34â†’  However, some users prefer to automatically get a newer version when they are published.
    35â†’* You are reliant on the GitHub CDN being available.
    36â†’
    37â†’[releases]: https://github.com/rust-lang/mdBook/releases
    38â†’
    39â†’### Building from source
    40â†’
    41â†’Building from source will require having Rust installed.
    42â†’Some services have Rust pre-installed, but if your service does not, you will need to add a step to install it.
    43â†’
    44â†’After Rust is installed, `cargo install` can be used to build and install mdBook.
    45â†’We recommend using a SemVer version specifier so that you get the latest **non-breaking** version of mdBook.
    46â†’For example:
    47â†’
    48â†’```sh
    49â†’cargo install mdbook --no-default-features --features search --vers "^0.4" --locked
    50â†’```
    51â†’
    52â†’This includes several recommended options:
    53â†’
    54â†’* `--no-default-features` --- Disables features like the HTTP server used by `mdbook serve` that is likely not needed on CI.
    55â†’  This will speed up the build time significantly.
    56â†’* `--features search` --- Disabling default features means you should then manually enable features that you want, such as the built-in [search] capability.
    57â†’* `--vers "^0.4"` --- This will install the most recent version of the `0.4` series.
    58â†’  However, versions after like `0.5.0` won't be installed, as they may break your build.
    59â†’  Cargo will automatically upgrade mdBook if you have an older version already installed.
    60â†’* `--locked` --- This will use the dependencies that were used when mdBook was released.
    61â†’  Without `--locked`, it will use the latest version of all dependencies, which may include some fixes since the last release, but may also (rarely) cause build problems.
    62â†’
    63â†’You will likely want to investigate caching options, as building mdBook can be somewhat slow.
    64â†’
    65â†’[search]: guide/reading.md#search
    66â†’
    67â†’## Running tests
    68â†’
    69â†’You may want to run tests using [`mdbook test`] every time you push a change or create a pull request.
    70â†’This can be used to validate Rust code examples in the book.
    71â†’
    72â†’This will require having Rust installed.
    73â†’Some services have Rust pre-installed, but if your service does not, you will need to add a step to install it.
    74â†’
    75â†’Other than making sure the appropriate version of Rust is installed, there's not much more than just running `mdbook test` from the book directory.
    76â†’
    77â†’You may also want to consider running other kinds of tests, like [mdbook-linkcheck] which will check for broken links.
    78â†’Or if you have your own style checks, spell checker, or any other tests it might be good to run them in CI.
    79â†’
    80â†’[`mdbook test`]: cli/test.md
    81â†’[mdbook-linkcheck]: https://github.com/Michael-F-Bryan/mdbook-linkcheck#continuous-integration
    82â†’
    83â†’## Deploying
    84â†’
    85â†’You may want to automatically deploy your book.
    86â†’Some may want to do this every time a change is pushed, and others may want to only deploy when a specific release is tagged.
    87â†’
    88â†’You'll also need to understand the specifics on how to push a change to your web service.
    89â†’For example, [GitHub Pages] just requires committing the output onto a specific git branch.
    90â†’Other services may require using something like SSH to connect to a remote server.
    91â†’
    92â†’The basic outline is that you need to run `mdbook build` to generate the output, and then transfer the files (which are in the `book` directory) to the correct location.
    93â†’
    94â†’You may then want to consider if you need to invalidate any caches on your web service.
    95â†’
    96â†’See the [Automated Deployment] wiki page for examples of various different services.
    97â†’
    98â†’[GitHub Pages]: https://docs.github.com/en/pages
    99â†’
   100â†’### 404 handling
   101â†’
   102â†’mdBook automatically generates a 404 page to be used for broken links.
   103â†’The default output is a file named `404.html` at the root of the book.
   104â†’Some services like [GitHub Pages] will automatically use this page for broken links.
   105â†’For other services, you may want to consider configuring the web server to use this page as it will provide the reader navigation to get back to the book.
   106â†’
   107â†’If your book is not deployed at the root of the domain, then you should set the [`output.html.site-url`] setting so that the 404 page works correctly.
   108â†’It needs to know where the book is deployed in order to load the static files (like CSS) correctly.
   109â†’For example, this guide is deployed at <https://rust-lang.github.io/mdBook/>, and the `site-url` setting is configured like this:
   110â†’
   111â†’```toml
   112â†’# book.toml
   113â†’[output.html]
   114â†’site-url = "/mdBook/"
   115â†’```
   116â†’
   117â†’You can customize the look of the 404 page by creating a file named `src/404.md` in your book.
   118â†’If you want to use a different filename, you can set [`output.html.input-404`] to a different filename.
   119â†’
   120â†’[`output.html.site-url`]: format/configuration/renderers.md#html-renderer-options
   121â†’[`output.html.input-404`]: format/configuration/renderers.md#html-renderer-options
for_developers/README.md
     1â†’# For developers
     2â†’
     3â†’While `mdbook` is mainly used as a command line tool, you can also import the
     4â†’underlying libraries directly and use those to manage a book. It also has a fairly
     5â†’flexible plugin mechanism, allowing you to create your own custom tooling and
     6â†’consumers (often referred to as *backends*) if you need to do some analysis of
     7â†’the book or render it in a different format.
     8â†’
     9â†’The *For Developers* chapters are here to show you the more advanced usage of
    10â†’`mdbook`.
    11â†’
    12â†’The two main ways a developer can hook into the book's build process is via,
    13â†’
    14â†’- [Preprocessors](preprocessors.md)
    15â†’- [Alternative Backends](backends.md)
    16â†’
    17â†’## The build process
    18â†’
    19â†’The process of rendering a book project goes through several steps.
    20â†’
    21â†’1. Load the book
    22â†’    - Parse the `book.toml`, falling back to the default `Config` if it doesn't
    23â†’       exist
    24â†’    - Load the book chapters into memory
    25â†’    - Discover which preprocessors/backends should be used
    26â†’2. For each backend:
    27â†’   1. Run all the preprocessors.
    28â†’   2. Call the backend to render the processed result.
    29â†’
    30â†’## Using `mdbook` as a library
    31â†’
    32â†’The `mdbook` binary is just a wrapper around the underlying mdBook crates,
    33â†’exposing their functionality as a command-line program. If you want to
    34â†’programmatically drive mdBook, you can use the [`mdbook-driver`] crate.
    35â†’This can be used to add your own functionality or tweak the build process.
    36â†’
    37â†’The easiest way to find out how to use the `mdbook-driver` crate is by looking at the
    38â†’[API Docs]. The top level documentation explains how one would use the
    39â†’[`MDBook`] type to load and build a book, while the [config] module gives a good
    40â†’explanation on the configuration system.
    41â†’
    42â†’[`MDBook`]: https://docs.rs/mdbook-driver/latest/mdbook_driver/struct.MDBook.html
    43â†’[API Docs]: https://docs.rs/mdbook-driver/latest/mdbook_driver/
    44â†’[config]: https://docs.rs/mdbook-driver/latest/mdbook_driver/config/index.html
for_developers/backends.md
     1â†’# Alternative backends
     2â†’
     3â†’A "backend" is simply a program which `mdbook` will invoke during the book
     4â†’rendering process. This program is passed a JSON representation of the book and
     5â†’configuration information via `stdin`. Once the backend receives this
     6â†’information it is free to do whatever it wants.
     7â†’
     8â†’See [Configuring Renderers](../format/configuration/renderers.md) for more information about using backends.
     9â†’
    10â†’The community has developed several backends.
    11â†’See the [Third Party Plugins] wiki page for a list of available backends.
    12â†’
    13â†’## Setting up
    14â†’
    15â†’This page will step you through creating your own alternative backend in the form
    16â†’of a simple word counting program. Although it will be written in Rust, there's
    17â†’no reason why it couldn't be accomplished using something like Python or Ruby.
    18â†’
    19â†’First you'll want to create a new binary program and add `mdbook-renderer` as a
    20â†’dependency.
    21â†’
    22â†’```shell
    23â†’$ cargo new --bin mdbook-wordcount
    24â†’$ cd mdbook-wordcount
    25â†’$ cargo add mdbook-renderer
    26â†’```
    27â†’
    28â†’When our `mdbook-wordcount` plugin is invoked, `mdbook` will send it a JSON
    29â†’version of [`RenderContext`] via our plugin's `stdin`. For convenience, there's
    30â†’a [`RenderContext::from_json()`] constructor which will load a `RenderContext`.
    31â†’
    32â†’This is all the boilerplate necessary for our backend to load the book.
    33â†’
    34â†’```rust
    35â†’// src/main.rs
    36â†’use std::io;
    37â†’use mdbook_renderer::RenderContext;
    38â†’
    39â†’fn main() {
    40â†’    let mut stdin = io::stdin();
    41â†’    let ctx = RenderContext::from_json(&mut stdin).unwrap();
    42â†’}
    43â†’```
    44â†’
    45â†’> **Note:** The `RenderContext` contains a `version` field. This lets backends
    46â†’> figure out whether they are compatible with the version of `mdbook` it's being
    47â†’> called by. This `version` comes directly from the corresponding field in
    48â†’> `mdbook`'s `Cargo.toml`.
    49â†’>
    50â†’> It is recommended that backends use the [`semver`] crate to inspect this field
    51â†’> and emit a warning if there may be a compatibility issue.
    52â†’
    53â†’## Inspecting the book
    54â†’
    55â†’Now our backend has a copy of the book, lets count how many words are in each
    56â†’chapter!
    57â†’
    58â†’Because the `RenderContext` contains a [`Book`] field (`book`), and a `Book` has
    59â†’the [`Book::iter()`] method for iterating over all items in a `Book`, this step
    60â†’turns out to be just as easy as the first.
    61â†’
    62â†’```rust
    63â†’
    64â†’fn main() {
    65â†’    let mut stdin = io::stdin();
    66â†’    let ctx = RenderContext::from_json(&mut stdin).unwrap();
    67â†’
    68â†’    for item in ctx.book.iter() {
    69â†’        if let BookItem::Chapter(ref ch) = *item {
    70â†’            let num_words = count_words(ch);
    71â†’            println!("{}: {}", ch.name, num_words);
    72â†’        }
    73â†’    }
    74â†’}
    75â†’
    76â†’fn count_words(ch: &Chapter) -> usize {
    77â†’    ch.content.split_whitespace().count()
    78â†’}
    79â†’```
    80â†’
    81â†’
    82â†’## Enabling the backend
    83â†’
    84â†’Now we've got the basics running, we want to actually use it. First, install the
    85â†’program.
    86â†’
    87â†’```shell
    88â†’$ cargo install --path .
    89â†’```
    90â†’
    91â†’Then `cd` to the particular book you'd like to count the words of and update its
    92â†’`book.toml` file.
    93â†’
    94â†’```diff
    95â†’  [book]
    96â†’  title = "mdBook Documentation"
    97â†’  description = "Create book from markdown files. Like Gitbook but implemented in Rust"
    98â†’  authors = ["Mathieu David", "Michael-F-Bryan"]
    99â†’
   100â†’+ [output.html]
   101â†’
   102â†’+ [output.wordcount]
   103â†’```
   104â†’
   105â†’When it loads a book into memory, `mdbook` will inspect your `book.toml` file to
   106â†’try and figure out which backends to use by looking for all `output.*` tables.
   107â†’If none are provided it'll fall back to using the default HTML renderer.
   108â†’
   109â†’Notably, this means if you want to add your own custom backend you'll also need
   110â†’to make sure to add the HTML backend, even if its table just stays empty.
   111â†’
   112â†’Now you just need to build your book like normal, and everything should *Just
   113â†’Work*.
   114â†’
   115â†’```shell
   116â†’$ mdbook build
   117â†’...
   118â†’2018-01-16 07:31:15 [INFO] (mdbook::renderer): Invoking the "mdbook-wordcount" renderer
   119â†’mdBook: 126
   120â†’Command Line Tool: 224
   121â†’init: 283
   122â†’build: 145
   123â†’watch: 146
   124â†’serve: 292
   125â†’test: 139
   126â†’Format: 30
   127â†’SUMMARY.md: 259
   128â†’Configuration: 784
   129â†’Theme: 304
   130â†’index.hbs: 447
   131â†’Syntax highlighting: 314
   132â†’MathJax Support: 153
   133â†’Rust code specific features: 148
   134â†’For Developers: 788
   135â†’Alternative Backends: 710
   136â†’Contributors: 85
   137â†’```
   138â†’
   139â†’The reason we didn't need to specify the full name/path of our `wordcount`
   140â†’backend is because `mdbook` will try to *infer* the program's name via
   141â†’convention. The executable for the `foo` backend is typically called
   142â†’`mdbook-foo`, with an associated `[output.foo]` entry in the `book.toml`. To
   143â†’explicitly tell `mdbook` what command to invoke (it may require command-line
   144â†’arguments or be an interpreted script), you can use the `command` field.
   145â†’
   146â†’```diff
   147â†’  [book]
   148â†’  title = "mdBook Documentation"
   149â†’  description = "Create book from markdown files. Like Gitbook but implemented in Rust"
   150â†’  authors = ["Mathieu David", "Michael-F-Bryan"]
   151â†’
   152â†’  [output.html]
   153â†’
   154â†’  [output.wordcount]
   155â†’+ command = "python /path/to/wordcount.py"
   156â†’```
   157â†’
   158â†’
   159â†’## Configuration
   160â†’
   161â†’Now imagine you don't want to count the number of words on a particular chapter
   162â†’(it might be generated text/code, etc). The canonical way to do this is via the
   163â†’usual `book.toml` configuration file by adding items to your `[output.foo]`
   164â†’table.
   165â†’
   166â†’The `Config` can be treated roughly as a nested hashmap which lets you call
   167â†’methods like `get()` to access the config's contents, with a
   168â†’`get_deserialized()` convenience method for retrieving a value and automatically
   169â†’deserializing to some arbitrary type `T`.
   170â†’
   171â†’To implement this, we'll create our own serializable `WordcountConfig` struct
   172â†’which will encapsulate all configuration for this backend.
   173â†’
   174â†’First add `serde` and `serde_derive` to your `Cargo.toml`,
   175â†’
   176â†’```
   177â†’$ cargo add serde serde_derive
   178â†’```
   179â†’
   180â†’And then you can create the config struct,
   181â†’
   182â†’```rust
   183â†’use serde_derive::{Serialize, Deserialize};
   184â†’
   185â†’...
   186â†’
   187â†’#[derive(Debug, Default, Serialize, Deserialize)]
   188â†’#[serde(default, rename_all = "kebab-case")]
   189â†’pub struct WordcountConfig {
   190â†’  pub ignores: Vec<String>,
   191â†’}
   192â†’```
   193â†’
   194â†’Now we just need to deserialize the `WordcountConfig` from our `RenderContext`
   195â†’and then add a check to make sure we skip ignored chapters.
   196â†’
   197â†’```diff
   198â†’  fn main() {
   199â†’      let mut stdin = io::stdin();
   200â†’      let ctx = RenderContext::from_json(&mut stdin).unwrap();
   201â†’+     let cfg: WordcountConfig = ctx.config
   202â†’+         .get_deserialized("output.wordcount")
   203â†’+         .unwrap_or_default();
   204â†’
   205â†’      for item in ctx.book.iter() {
   206â†’          if let BookItem::Chapter(ref ch) = *item {
   207â†’+             if cfg.ignores.contains(&ch.name) {
   208â†’+                 continue;
   209â†’+             }
   210â†’+
   211â†’              let num_words = count_words(ch);
   212â†’              println!("{}: {}", ch.name, num_words);
   213â†’          }
   214â†’      }
   215â†’  }
   216â†’```
   217â†’
   218â†’
   219â†’## Output and signalling failure
   220â†’
   221â†’While it's nice to print word counts to the terminal when a book is built, it
   222â†’might also be a good idea to output them to a file somewhere. `mdbook` tells a
   223â†’backend where it should place any generated output via the `destination` field
   224â†’in [`RenderContext`].
   225â†’
   226â†’```diff
   227â†’+ use std::fs::{self, File};
   228â†’+ use std::io::{self, Write};
   229â†’- use std::io;
   230â†’  use mdbook::renderer::RenderContext;
   231â†’  use mdbook::book::{BookItem, Chapter};
   232â†’
   233â†’  fn main() {
   234â†’    ...
   235â†’
   236â†’+     let _ = fs::create_dir_all(&ctx.destination);
   237â†’+     let mut f = File::create(ctx.destination.join("wordcounts.txt")).unwrap();
   238â†’+
   239â†’      for item in ctx.book.iter() {
   240â†’          if let BookItem::Chapter(ref ch) = *item {
   241â†’              ...
   242â†’
   243â†’              let num_words = count_words(ch);
   244â†’              println!("{}: {}", ch.name, num_words);
   245â†’+             writeln!(f, "{}: {}", ch.name, num_words).unwrap();
   246â†’          }
   247â†’      }
   248â†’  }
   249â†’```
   250â†’
   251â†’> **Note:** There is no guarantee that the destination directory exists or is
   252â†’> empty (`mdbook` may leave the previous contents to let backends do caching),
   253â†’> so it's always a good idea to create it with `fs::create_dir_all()`.
   254â†’>
   255â†’> If the destination directory already exists, don't assume it will be empty.
   256â†’> To allow backends to cache the results from previous runs, `mdbook` may leave
   257â†’> old content in the directory.
   258â†’
   259â†’There's always the possibility that an error will occur while processing a book
   260â†’(just look at all the `unwrap()`'s we've written already), so `mdbook` will
   261â†’interpret a non-zero exit code as a rendering failure.
   262â†’
   263â†’For example, if we wanted to make sure all chapters have an *even* number of
   264â†’words, erroring out if an odd number is encountered, then you may do something
   265â†’like this:
   266â†’
   267â†’```diff
   268â†’+ use std::process;
   269â†’  ...
   270â†’
   271â†’  fn main() {
   272â†’      ...
   273â†’
   274â†’      for item in ctx.book.iter() {
   275â†’          if let BookItem::Chapter(ref ch) = *item {
   276â†’              ...
   277â†’
   278â†’              let num_words = count_words(ch);
   279â†’              println!("{}: {}", ch.name, num_words);
   280â†’              writeln!(f, "{}: {}", ch.name, num_words).unwrap();
   281â†’
   282â†’+             if cfg.deny_odds && num_words % 2 == 1 {
   283â†’+               eprintln!("{} has an odd number of words!", ch.name);
   284â†’+               process::exit(1);
   285â†’+             }
   286â†’          }
   287â†’      }
   288â†’  }
   289â†’
   290â†’  #[derive(Debug, Default, Serialize, Deserialize)]
   291â†’  #[serde(default, rename_all = "kebab-case")]
   292â†’  pub struct WordcountConfig {
   293â†’      pub ignores: Vec<String>,
   294â†’+     pub deny_odds: bool,
   295â†’  }
   296â†’```
   297â†’
   298â†’Now, if we reinstall the backend and build a book,
   299â†’
   300â†’```shell
   301â†’$ cargo install --path . --force
   302â†’$ mdbook build /path/to/book
   303â†’...
   304â†’2018-01-16 21:21:39 [INFO] (mdbook::renderer): Invoking the "wordcount" renderer
   305â†’mdBook: 126
   306â†’Command Line Tool: 224
   307â†’init: 283
   308â†’init has an odd number of words!
   309â†’2018-01-16 21:21:39 [ERROR] (mdbook::renderer): Renderer exited with non-zero return code.
   310â†’2018-01-16 21:21:39 [ERROR] (mdbook::utils): Error: Rendering failed
   311â†’2018-01-16 21:21:39 [ERROR] (mdbook::utils):    Caused By: The "mdbook-wordcount" renderer failed
   312â†’```
   313â†’
   314â†’As you've probably already noticed, output from the plugin's subprocess is
   315â†’immediately passed through to the user. It is encouraged for plugins to follow
   316â†’the "rule of silence" and only generate output when necessary (e.g. an error in
   317â†’generation or a warning).
   318â†’
   319â†’All environment variables are passed through to the backend, allowing you to use
   320â†’the usual `MDBOOK_LOG` to control logging verbosity.
   321â†’
   322â†’## Wrapping up
   323â†’
   324â†’Although contrived, hopefully this example was enough to show how you'd create
   325â†’an alternative backend for `mdbook`. If you feel it's missing something, don't
   326â†’hesitate to create an issue in the [issue tracker] so we can improve the user
   327â†’guide.
   328â†’
   329â†’The existing backends mentioned towards the start of this chapter should serve
   330â†’as a good example of how it's done in real life, so feel free to skim through
   331â†’the source code or ask questions.
   332â†’
   333â†’
   334â†’[Third Party Plugins]: https://github.com/rust-lang/mdBook/wiki/Third-party-plugins
   335â†’[`RenderContext`]: https://docs.rs/mdbook-renderer/latest/mdbook_renderer/struct.RenderContext.html
   336â†’[`RenderContext::from_json()`]: https://docs.rs/mdbook-renderer/latest/mdbook_renderer/struct.RenderContext.html#method.from_json
   337â†’[`semver`]: https://crates.io/crates/semver
   338â†’[`Book`]: https://docs.rs/mdbook-renderer/latest/mdbook_renderer/book/struct.Book.html
   339â†’[`Book::iter()`]: https://docs.rs/mdbook-renderer/latest/mdbook_renderer/book/struct.Book.html#method.iter
   340â†’[`Config`]: https://docs.rs/mdbook-renderer/latest/mdbook_renderer/config/struct.Config.html
   341â†’[issue tracker]: https://github.com/rust-lang/mdBook/issues
for_developers/mdbook-wordcount/src/main.rs
    12â†’fn main() {
    40â†’fn count_words(ch: &Chapter) -> usize {
    44â†’#[derive(Debug, Default, Serialize, Deserialize)]
    45â†’#[serde(default, rename_all = "kebab-case")]
    46â†’pub struct WordcountConfig {
    47â†’    pub ignores: Vec<String>,
    48â†’    pub deny_odds: bool,
    49â†’}
for_developers/preprocessors.md
     1â†’# Preprocessors
     2â†’
     3â†’A *preprocessor* is simply a bit of code which gets run immediately after the
     4â†’book is loaded and before it gets rendered, allowing you to update and mutate
     5â†’the book. Possible use cases are:
     6â†’
     7â†’- Creating custom helpers like `\{{#include /path/to/file.md}}`
     8â†’- Substituting in latex-style expressions (`$$ \frac{1}{3} $$`) with their
     9â†’  mathjax equivalents
    10â†’
    11â†’See [Configuring Preprocessors](../format/configuration/preprocessors.md) for more information about using preprocessors.
    12â†’
    13â†’## Hooking into MDBook
    14â†’
    15â†’MDBook uses a fairly simple mechanism for discovering third party plugins.
    16â†’A new table is added to `book.toml` (e.g. `[preprocessor.foo]` for the `foo`
    17â†’preprocessor) and then `mdbook` will try to invoke the `mdbook-foo` program as
    18â†’part of the build process.
    19â†’
    20â†’Once the preprocessor has been defined and the build process starts, mdBook executes the command defined in the `preprocessor.foo.command` key twice.
    21â†’The first time it runs the preprocessor to determine if it supports the given renderer.
    22â†’mdBook passes two arguments to the process: the first argument is the string `supports` and the second argument is the renderer name.
    23â†’The preprocessor should exit with a status code 0 if it supports the given renderer, or return a non-zero exit code if it does not.
    24â†’
    25â†’If the preprocessor supports the renderer, then mdbook runs it a second time, passing JSON data into stdin.
    26â†’The JSON consists of an array of `[context, book]` where `context` is the serialized object [`PreprocessorContext`] and `book` is a [`Book`] object containing the content of the book.
    27â†’
    28â†’The preprocessor should return the JSON format of the [`Book`] object to stdout, with any modifications it wishes to perform.
    29â†’
    30â†’The easiest way to get started is by creating your own implementation of the
    31â†’`Preprocessor` trait (e.g. in `lib.rs`) and then creating a shell binary which
    32â†’translates inputs to the correct `Preprocessor` method. For convenience, there
    33â†’is [an example no-op preprocessor] in the `examples/` directory which can easily
    34â†’be adapted for other preprocessors.
    35â†’
    36â†’<details>
    37â†’<summary>Example no-op preprocessor</summary>
    38â†’
    39â†’```rust
    40â†’// nop-preprocessors.rs
    41â†’
    42â†’{{#include ../../../examples/nop-preprocessor.rs}}
    43â†’```
    44â†’</details>
    45â†’
    46â†’## Hints for implementing a preprocessor
    47â†’
    48â†’By pulling in `mdbook-preprocessor` as a library, preprocessors can have access to the
    49â†’existing infrastructure for dealing with books.
    50â†’
    51â†’For example, a custom preprocessor could use the
    52â†’[`parse_input()`] function to deserialize the JSON written to
    53â†’`stdin`. Then each chapter of the `Book` can be mutated in-place via
    54â†’[`Book::for_each_mut()`], and then written to `stdout` with the `serde_json`
    55â†’crate.
    56â†’
    57â†’Chapters can be accessed either directly (by recursively iterating over
    58â†’chapters) or via the `Book::for_each_mut()` convenience method.
    59â†’
    60â†’The `chapter.content` is just a string which happens to be markdown. While it's
    61â†’entirely possible to use regular expressions or do a manual find & replace,
    62â†’you'll probably want to process the input into something more computer-friendly.
    63â†’The [`mdbook-markdown`] crate exposes the [`pulldown-cmark`][pc] crate used by mdBook to parse Markdown. The [`pulldown-cmark-to-cmark`][pctc] crate can be used to translate events back into markdown text.
    64â†’
    65â†’The following code block shows how to remove all emphasis from markdown,
    66â†’without accidentally breaking the document.
    67â†’
    68â†’```rust
    69â†’{{#rustdoc_include ../../../examples/remove-emphasis/mdbook-remove-emphasis/src/main.rs:remove_emphasis}}
    70â†’```
    71â†’
    72â†’Take a look at the [full example source][emphasis-example] for more details.
    73â†’
    74â†’## Implementing a preprocessor with a different language
    75â†’
    76â†’The fact that mdBook utilizes stdin and stdout to communicate with the preprocessors makes it easy to implement them in a language other than Rust.
    77â†’The following code shows how to implement a simple preprocessor in Python, which will modify the content of the first chapter.
    78â†’The example below follows the configuration shown above with `preprocessor.foo.command` actually pointing to a Python script.
    79â†’
    80â†’```python
    81â†’import json
    82â†’import sys
    83â†’
    84â†’
    85â†’if __name__ == '__main__':
    86â†’    if len(sys.argv) > 1: # we check if we received any argument
    87â†’        if sys.argv[1] == "supports": 
    88â†’            # then we are good to return an exit status code of 0, since the other argument will just be the renderer's name
    89â†’            sys.exit(0)
    90â†’
    91â†’    # load both the context and the book representations from stdin
    92â†’    context, book = json.load(sys.stdin)
    93â†’    # and now, we can just modify the content of the first chapter
    94â†’    book['items'][0]['Chapter']['content'] = '# Hello'
    95â†’    # we are done with the book's modification, we can just print it to stdout, 
    96â†’    print(json.dumps(book))
    97â†’```
    98â†’
    99â†’
   100â†’[emphasis-example]: https://github.com/rust-lang/mdBook/tree/master/examples/remove-emphasis/
   101â†’[pc]: https://crates.io/crates/pulldown-cmark
   102â†’[pctc]: https://crates.io/crates/pulldown-cmark-to-cmark
   103â†’[an example no-op preprocessor]: https://github.com/rust-lang/mdBook/blob/master/examples/nop-preprocessor.rs
   104â†’[`parse_input()`]: https://docs.rs/mdbook-preprocessor/latest/mdbook_preprocessor/fn.parse_input.html
   105â†’[`Book::for_each_mut()`]: https://docs.rs/mdbook-preprocessor/latest/mdbook_preprocessor/book/struct.Book.html#method.for_each_mut
   106â†’[`PreprocessorContext`]: https://docs.rs/mdbook-preprocessor/latest/mdbook_preprocessor/struct.PreprocessorContext.html
   107â†’[`Book`]: https://docs.rs/mdbook-preprocessor/latest/mdbook_preprocessor/book/struct.Book.html
   108â†’[`mdbook-markdown`]: https://docs.rs/mdbook-markdown/latest/mdbook_markdown/
format/README.md
     1â†’# Format
     2â†’
     3â†’In this section you will learn how to:
     4â†’
     5â†’- Structure your book correctly
     6â†’- Format your `SUMMARY.md` file
     7â†’- Configure your book using `book.toml`
     8â†’- Customize your theme
format/configuration/README.md
     1â†’# Configuration
     2â†’
     3â†’This section details the configuration options available in the ***book.toml***:
     4â†’- **[General]** configuration including the `book`, `rust`, `build` sections
     5â†’- **[Preprocessor]** configuration for default and custom book preprocessors
     6â†’- **[Renderer]** configuration for the HTML, Markdown and custom renderers
     7â†’- **[Environment Variable]** configuration for overriding configuration options in your environment
     8â†’
     9â†’[General]: general.md
    10â†’[Preprocessor]: preprocessors.md
    11â†’[Renderer]: renderers.md
    12â†’[Environment Variable]: environment-variables.md
format/configuration/environment-variables.md
     1â†’# Environment variables
     2â†’
     3â†’All configuration values can be overridden from the command line by setting the
     4â†’corresponding environment variable. Because many operating systems restrict
     5â†’environment variables to be alphanumeric characters or `_`, the configuration
     6â†’key needs to be formatted slightly differently to the normal `foo.bar.baz` form.
     7â†’
     8â†’Variables starting with `MDBOOK_` are used for configuration. The key is created
     9â†’by removing the `MDBOOK_` prefix and turning the resulting string into
    10â†’`kebab-case`. Double underscores (`__`) separate nested keys, while a single
    11â†’underscore (`_`) is replaced with a dash (`-`).
    12â†’
    13â†’For example:
    14â†’
    15â†’- `MDBOOK_book` -> `book`
    16â†’- `MDBOOK_BOOK` -> `book`
    17â†’- `MDBOOK_BOOK__TITLE` -> `book.title`
    18â†’- `MDBOOK_BOOK__TEXT_DIRECTION` -> `book.text-direction`
    19â†’
    20â†’So by setting the `MDBOOK_BOOK__TITLE` environment variable you can override the
    21â†’book's title without needing to touch your `book.toml`.
    22â†’
    23â†’> **Note:** To facilitate setting more complex config items, the value of an
    24â†’> environment variable is first parsed as JSON, falling back to a string if the
    25â†’> parse fails.
    26â†’>
    27â†’> This means, if you so desired, you could override all book metadata when
    28â†’> building the book with something like
    29â†’>
    30â†’> ```shell
    31â†’> $ export MDBOOK_BOOK='{"title": "My Awesome Book", "authors": ["Michael-F-Bryan"]}'
    32â†’> $ mdbook build
    33â†’> ```
    34â†’
    35â†’The latter case may be useful in situations where `mdbook` is invoked from a
    36â†’script or CI, where it sometimes isn't possible to update the `book.toml` before
    37â†’building.
format/configuration/general.md
     1â†’# General configuration
     2â†’
     3â†’You can configure the parameters for your book in the ***book.toml*** file.
     4â†’
     5â†’Here is an example of what a ***book.toml*** file might look like:
     6â†’
     7â†’```toml
     8â†’[book]
     9â†’title = "Example book"
    10â†’authors = ["John Doe"]
    11â†’description = "The example book covers examples."
    12â†’
    13â†’[rust]
    14â†’edition = "2018"
    15â†’
    16â†’[build]
    17â†’build-dir = "my-example-book"
    18â†’create-missing = false
    19â†’
    20â†’[preprocessor.index]
    21â†’
    22â†’[preprocessor.links]
    23â†’
    24â†’[output.html]
    25â†’additional-css = ["custom.css"]
    26â†’
    27â†’[output.html.search]
    28â†’limit-results = 15
    29â†’```
    30â†’
    31â†’## Supported configuration options
    32â†’
    33â†’It is important to note that **any** relative path specified in the
    34â†’configuration will always be taken relative from the root of the book where the
    35â†’configuration file is located.
    36â†’
    37â†’### General metadata
    38â†’
    39â†’This is general information about your book.
    40â†’
    41â†’- **title:** The title of the book
    42â†’- **authors:** The author(s) of the book
    43â†’- **description:** A description for the book, which is added as meta
    44â†’  information in the html `<head>` of each page
    45â†’- **src:** By default, the source directory is found in the directory named
    46â†’  `src` directly under the root folder. But this is configurable with the `src`
    47â†’  key in the configuration file.
    48â†’- **language:** The main language of the book, which is used as a language attribute `<html lang="en">` for example.
    49â†’  This is also used to derive the direction of text (RTL, LTR) within the book.
    50â†’- **text-direction**: The direction of text in the book: Left-to-right (LTR) or Right-to-left (RTL). Possible values: `ltr`, `rtl`.
    51â†’  When not specified, the text direction is derived from the book's `language` attribute.
    52â†’
    53â†’**book.toml**
    54â†’```toml
    55â†’[book]
    56â†’title = "Example book"
    57â†’authors = ["John Doe", "Jane Doe"]
    58â†’description = "The example book covers examples."
    59â†’src = "my-src"  # the source files will be found in `root/my-src` instead of `root/src`
    60â†’language = "en"
    61â†’text-direction = "ltr"
    62â†’```
    63â†’
    64â†’### Rust options
    65â†’
    66â†’Options for the Rust language, relevant to running tests and playground
    67â†’integration.
    68â†’
    69â†’```toml
    70â†’[rust]
    71â†’edition = "2015"   # the default edition for code blocks
    72â†’```
    73â†’
    74â†’- **edition**: Rust edition to use by default for the code snippets. Default
    75â†’  is `"2015"`. Individual code blocks can be controlled with the `edition2015`,
    76â†’  `edition2018`, `edition2021` or `edition2024` annotations, such as:
    77â†’
    78â†’  ~~~text
    79â†’  ```rust,edition2015
    80â†’  // This only works in 2015.
    81â†’  let try = true;
    82â†’  ```
    83â†’  ~~~
    84â†’
    85â†’### Build options
    86â†’
    87â†’This controls the build process of your book.
    88â†’
    89â†’```toml
    90â†’[build]
    91â†’build-dir = "book"                # the directory where the output is placed
    92â†’create-missing = true             # whether or not to create missing pages
    93â†’use-default-preprocessors = true  # use the default preprocessors
    94â†’extra-watch-dirs = []             # directories to watch for triggering builds
    95â†’```
    96â†’
    97â†’- **build-dir:** The directory to put the rendered book in. By default this is
    98â†’  `book/` in the book's root directory.
    99â†’  This can overridden with the `--dest-dir` CLI option.
   100â†’- **create-missing:** By default, any missing files specified in `SUMMARY.md`
   101â†’  will be created when the book is built (i.e. `create-missing = true`). If this
   102â†’  is `false` then the build process will instead exit with an error if any files
   103â†’  do not exist.
   104â†’- **use-default-preprocessors:** Disable the default preprocessors (of `links` &
   105â†’  `index`) by setting this option to `false`.
   106â†’
   107â†’  If you have the same, and/or other preprocessors declared via their table
   108â†’  of configuration, they will run instead.
   109â†’
   110â†’  - For clarity, with no preprocessor configuration, the default `links` and
   111â†’    `index` will run.
   112â†’  - Setting `use-default-preprocessors = false` will disable these
   113â†’    default preprocessors from running.
   114â†’  - Adding `[preprocessor.links]`, for example, will ensure, regardless of
   115â†’    `use-default-preprocessors` that `links` it will run.
   116â†’- **extra-watch-dirs**: A list of paths to directories that will be watched in
   117â†’  the `watch` and `serve` commands. Changes to files under these directories will
   118â†’  trigger rebuilds. Useful if your book depends on files outside its `src` directory.
format/configuration/preprocessors.md
     1â†’# Configuring Preprocessors
     2â†’
     3â†’Preprocessors are extensions that can modify the raw Markdown source before it gets sent to the renderer.
     4â†’
     5â†’The following preprocessors are built-in and included by default:
     6â†’
     7â†’- `links`: Expands the `{{ #playground }}`, `{{ #include }}`, and `{{ #rustdoc_include }}` handlebars
     8â†’  helpers in a chapter to include the contents of a file.
     9â†’  See [Including files] for more.
    10â†’- `index`: Convert all chapter files named `README.md` into `index.md`. That is
    11â†’  to say, all `README.md` would be rendered to an index file `index.html` in the
    12â†’  rendered book.
    13â†’
    14â†’The built-in preprocessors can be disabled with the [`build.use-default-preprocessors`] config option.
    15â†’
    16â†’The community has developed several preprocessors.
    17â†’See the [Third Party Plugins] wiki page for a list of available preprocessors.
    18â†’
    19â†’For information on how to create a new preprocessor, see the [Preprocessors for Developers] chapter.
    20â†’
    21â†’[Including files]: ../mdbook.md#including-files
    22â†’[`build.use-default-preprocessors`]: general.md#build-options
    23â†’[Third Party Plugins]: https://github.com/rust-lang/mdBook/wiki/Third-party-plugins
    24â†’[Preprocessors for Developers]: ../../for_developers/preprocessors.md
    25â†’
    26â†’## Custom preprocessor configuration
    27â†’
    28â†’Preprocessors can be added by including a `preprocessor` table in `book.toml` with the name of the preprocessor.
    29â†’For example, if you have a preprocessor called `mdbook-example`, then you can include it with:
    30â†’
    31â†’```toml
    32â†’[preprocessor.example]
    33â†’```
    34â†’
    35â†’With this table, mdBook will execute the `mdbook-example` preprocessor.
    36â†’
    37â†’This table can include additional key-value pairs that are specific to the preprocessor.
    38â†’For example, if our example preprocessor needed some extra configuration options:
    39â†’
    40â†’```toml
    41â†’[preprocessor.example]
    42â†’some-extra-feature = true
    43â†’```
    44â†’
    45â†’## Locking a preprocessor dependency to a renderer
    46â†’
    47â†’You can explicitly specify that a preprocessor should run for a renderer by
    48â†’binding the two together.
    49â†’
    50â†’```toml
    51â†’[preprocessor.example]
    52â†’renderers = ["html"]  # example preprocessor only runs with the HTML renderer
    53â†’```
    54â†’
    55â†’## Provide your own command
    56â†’
    57â†’By default when you add a `[preprocessor.foo]` table to your `book.toml` file,
    58â†’`mdbook` will try to invoke the `mdbook-foo` executable. If you want to use a
    59â†’different program name or pass in command-line arguments, this behaviour can
    60â†’be overridden by adding a `command` field.
    61â†’
    62â†’```toml
    63â†’[preprocessor.random]
    64â†’command = "python random.py"
    65â†’```
    66â†’
    67â†’### Optional preprocessors
    68â†’
    69â†’If you enable a preprocessor that isn't installed, the default behavior is to throw an error.
    70â†’This behavior can be changed by marking the preprocessor as optional:
    71â†’
    72â†’```toml
    73â†’[preprocessor.example]
    74â†’optional = true
    75â†’```
    76â†’
    77â†’This demotes the error to a warning.
    78â†’
    79â†’## Require a certain order
    80â†’
    81â†’The order in which preprocessors are run can be controlled with the `before` and `after` fields.
    82â†’For example, suppose you want your `linenos` preprocessor to process lines that may have been `{{#include}}`d; then you want it to run after the built-in `links` preprocessor, which you can require using either the `before` or `after` field:
    83â†’
    84â†’```toml
    85â†’[preprocessor.linenos]
    86â†’after = [ "links" ]
    87â†’```
    88â†’
    89â†’or
    90â†’
    91â†’```toml
    92â†’[preprocessor.links]
    93â†’before = [ "linenos" ]
    94â†’```
    95â†’
    96â†’It would also be possible, though redundant, to specify both of the above in the same config file.
    97â†’
    98â†’Preprocessors having the same priority specified through `before` and `after` are sorted by name.
    99â†’Any infinite loops will be detected and produce an error.
format/configuration/renderers.md
     1â†’# Configuring Renderers
     2â†’
     3â†’Renderers (also called "backends") are responsible for creating the output of the book.
     4â†’
     5â†’The following backends are built-in:
     6â†’
     7â†’* [`html`](#html-renderer-options) --- This renders the book to HTML.
     8â†’  This is enabled by default if no other `[output]` tables are defined in `book.toml`.
     9â†’* [`markdown`](#markdown-renderer) --- This outputs the book as markdown after running the preprocessors.
    10â†’  This is useful for debugging preprocessors.
    11â†’
    12â†’The community has developed several backends.
    13â†’See the [Third Party Plugins] wiki page for a list of available backends.
    14â†’
    15â†’For information on how to create a new backend, see the [Backends for Developers] chapter.
    16â†’
    17â†’[Third Party Plugins]: https://github.com/rust-lang/mdBook/wiki/Third-party-plugins
    18â†’[Backends for Developers]: ../../for_developers/backends.md
    19â†’
    20â†’## Output tables
    21â†’
    22â†’Backends can be added by including a `output` table in `book.toml` with the name of the backend.
    23â†’For example, if you have a backend called `mdbook-wordcount`, then you can include it with:
    24â†’
    25â†’```toml
    26â†’[output.wordcount]
    27â†’```
    28â†’
    29â†’With this table, mdBook will execute the `mdbook-wordcount` backend.
    30â†’
    31â†’This table can include additional key-value pairs that are specific to the backend.
    32â†’For example, if our example backend needed some extra configuration options:
    33â†’
    34â†’```toml
    35â†’[output.wordcount]
    36â†’ignores = ["Example Chapter"]
    37â†’```
    38â†’
    39â†’If you define any `[output]` tables, then the `html` backend is not enabled by default.
    40â†’If you want to keep the `html` backend running, then just include it in the `book.toml` file.
    41â†’For example:
    42â†’
    43â†’```toml
    44â†’[book]
    45â†’title = "My Awesome Book"
    46â†’
    47â†’[output.wordcount]
    48â†’
    49â†’[output.html]
    50â†’```
    51â†’
    52â†’If more than one `output` table is included, this changes the behavior for the layout of the output directory.
    53â†’If there is only one backend, then it places its output directly in the `book` directory (see [`build.build-dir`] to override this location).
    54â†’If there is more than one backend, then each backend is placed in a separate directory underneath `book`.
    55â†’For example, the above would have directories `book/html` and `book/wordcount`.
    56â†’
    57â†’[`build.build-dir`]: general.md#build-options
    58â†’
    59â†’### Custom backend commands
    60â†’
    61â†’By default when you add an `[output.foo]` table to your `book.toml` file,
    62â†’`mdbook` will try to invoke the `mdbook-foo` executable.
    63â†’If you want to use a different program name or pass in command-line arguments,
    64â†’this behaviour can be overridden by adding a `command` field.
    65â†’
    66â†’```toml
    67â†’[output.random]
    68â†’command = "python random.py"
    69â†’```
    70â†’
    71â†’### Optional backends
    72â†’
    73â†’If you enable a backend that isn't installed, the default behavior is to throw an error.
    74â†’This behavior can be changed by marking the backend as optional:
    75â†’
    76â†’```toml
    77â†’[output.wordcount]
    78â†’optional = true
    79â†’```
    80â†’
    81â†’This demotes the error to a warning.
    82â†’
    83â†’
    84â†’## HTML renderer options
    85â†’
    86â†’The HTML renderer has a variety of options detailed below.
    87â†’They should be specified in the `[output.html]` table of the `book.toml` file.
    88â†’
    89â†’```toml
    90â†’# Example book.toml file with all output options.
    91â†’[book]
    92â†’title = "Example book"
    93â†’authors = ["John Doe", "Jane Doe"]
    94â†’description = "The example book covers examples."
    95â†’
    96â†’[output.html]
    97â†’theme = "my-theme"
    98â†’default-theme = "light"
    99â†’preferred-dark-theme = "navy"
   100â†’smart-punctuation = true
   101â†’definition-lists = true
   102â†’admonitions = true
   103â†’mathjax-support = false
   104â†’additional-css = ["custom.css", "custom2.css"]
   105â†’additional-js = ["custom.js"]
   106â†’no-section-label = false
   107â†’git-repository-url = "https://github.com/rust-lang/mdBook"
   108â†’git-repository-icon = "fab-github"
   109â†’edit-url-template = "https://github.com/rust-lang/mdBook/edit/master/guide/{path}"
   110â†’site-url = "/example-book/"
   111â†’cname = "myproject.rs"
   112â†’input-404 = "not-found.md"
   113â†’sidebar-header-nav = true
   114â†’```
   115â†’
   116â†’The following configuration options are available:
   117â†’
   118â†’- **theme:** mdBook comes with a default theme and all the resource files needed
   119â†’  for it. But if this option is set, mdBook will selectively overwrite the theme
   120â†’  files with the ones found in the specified folder.
   121â†’- **default-theme:** The theme color scheme to select by default in the
   122â†’  'Change Theme' dropdown. Defaults to `light`.
   123â†’- **preferred-dark-theme:** The default dark theme. This theme will be used if
   124â†’  the browser requests the dark version of the site via the
   125â†’  [`prefers-color-scheme`](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/CSS/@media/prefers-color-scheme)
   126â†’  CSS media query. Defaults to `navy`.
   127â†’- **smart-punctuation:** Converts quotes to curly quotes, `...` to `â€¦`, `--` to en-dash, and `---` to em-dash.
   128â†’  See [Smart Punctuation](../markdown.md#smart-punctuation).
   129â†’  Defaults to `true`.
   130â†’- **definition-lists:** Enables [definition lists](../markdown.md#definition-lists). Defaults to `true`.
   131â†’- **admonitions:** Enables [admonitions](../markdown.md#admonitions). Defaults to `true`.
   132â†’- **mathjax-support:** Adds support for [MathJax](../mathjax.md). Defaults to
   133â†’  `false`.
   134â†’- **additional-css:** If you need to slightly change the appearance of your book
   135â†’  without overwriting the whole style, you can specify a set of stylesheets that
   136â†’  will be loaded after the default ones where you can surgically change the
   137â†’  style.
   138â†’- **additional-js:** If you need to add some behaviour to your book without
   139â†’  removing the current behaviour, you can specify a set of JavaScript files that
   140â†’  will be loaded alongside the default one.
   141â†’- **no-section-label:** mdBook by defaults adds numeric section labels in the table of
   142â†’  contents column. For example, "1.", "2.1". Set this option to true to disable
   143â†’  those labels. Defaults to `false`.
   144â†’- **git-repository-url:**  A url to the git repository for the book. If provided
   145â†’  an icon link will be output in the menu bar of the book.
   146â†’- **git-repository-icon:** The Font Awesome icon class to use for the git repository link. Defaults to `fab-github` which looks like <i class="fab fa-github"></i>. If you are not using GitHub, another option to consider is `fas-code-fork` which looks like <i class="fas fa-code-fork"></i>. The start of the string should be `fa-` for regular icons, `fas-` for solid icons, or `fab-` for brand icons. See the [free icon set](https://fontawesome.com/v6/search) for the available icons.
   147â†’- **edit-url-template:** Edit url template, when provided shows a
   148â†’  "Suggest an edit" button (which looks like <i class="fas fa-pencil"></i>) for directly jumping to editing the currently
   149â†’  viewed page. For e.g. GitHub projects set this to
   150â†’  `https://github.com/<owner>/<repo>/edit/<branch>/{path}` or for
   151â†’  Bitbucket projects set it to
   152â†’  `https://bitbucket.org/<owner>/<repo>/src/<branch>/{path}?mode=edit`
   153â†’  where {path} will be replaced with the full path of the file in the
   154â†’  repository.
   155â†’- **input-404:** The name of the markdown file used for missing files.
   156â†’  The corresponding output file will be the same, with the extension replaced with `html`.
   157â†’  Defaults to `404.md`.
   158â†’- **site-url:** The url where the book will be hosted. This is required to ensure
   159â†’  navigation links and script/css imports in the 404 file work correctly, even when accessing
   160â†’  urls in subdirectories. Defaults to `/`. If `site-url` is set,
   161â†’  make sure to use document relative links for your assets, meaning they should not start with `/`.
   162â†’- **cname:** The DNS subdomain or apex domain at which your book will be hosted.
   163â†’  This string will be written to a file named CNAME in the root of your site, as
   164â†’  required by GitHub Pages (see [*Managing a custom domain for your GitHub Pages
   165â†’  site*][custom domain]).
   166â†’- **hash-files:** Include a cryptographic "fingerprint" of the files' contents in static asset filenames,
   167â†’  so that if the contents of the file are changed, the name of the file will also change.
   168â†’  For example, `css/chrome.css` may become `css/chrome-9b8f428e.css`.
   169â†’  Chapter HTML files are not renamed.
   170â†’  Static CSS and JS files can reference each other using `{{ resource "filename" }}` directives.
   171â†’  Defaults to `true`.
   172â†’- **sidebar-header-nav:** If `true`, the sidebar will contain navigation for headers on the current page. Default is `true`.
   173â†’
   174â†’[custom domain]: https://docs.github.com/en/github/working-with-github-pages/managing-a-custom-domain-for-your-github-pages-site
   175â†’
   176â†’### `[output.html.print]`
   177â†’
   178â†’The `[output.html.print]` table provides options for controlling the printable output.
   179â†’By default, mdBook will include an icon on the top right of the book (which looks like <i class="fas fa-print"></i>) that will print the book as a single page.
   180â†’
   181â†’```toml
   182â†’[output.html.print]
   183â†’enable = true    # include support for printable output
   184â†’page-break = true # insert page-break after each chapter
   185â†’```
   186â†’
   187â†’- **enable:** Enable print support. When `false`, all print support will not be
   188â†’  rendered. Defaults to `true`.
   189â†’- **page-break:** Insert page breaks between chapters. Defaults to `true`.
   190â†’
   191â†’### `[output.html.fold]`
   192â†’
   193â†’The `[output.html.fold]` table provides options for controlling folding of the chapter listing in the navigation sidebar.
   194â†’
   195â†’```toml
   196â†’[output.html.fold]
   197â†’enable = false    # whether or not to enable section folding
   198â†’level = 0         # the depth to start folding
   199â†’```
   200â†’
   201â†’- **enable:** Enable section-folding. When off, all folds are open.
   202â†’  Defaults to `false`.
   203â†’- **level:** The higher the more folded regions are open. When level is 0, all
   204â†’  folds are closed. Defaults to `0`.
   205â†’
   206â†’### `[output.html.playground]`
   207â†’
   208â†’The `[output.html.playground]` table provides options for controlling Rust sample code blocks, and their integration with the [Rust Playground].
   209â†’
   210â†’[Rust Playground]: https://play.rust-lang.org/
   211â†’
   212â†’```toml
   213â†’[output.html.playground]
   214â†’editable = false         # allows editing the source code
   215â†’copyable = true          # include the copy button for copying code snippets
   216â†’copy-js = true           # includes the JavaScript for the code editor
   217â†’line-numbers = false     # displays line numbers for editable code
   218â†’runnable = true          # displays a run button for rust code
   219â†’```
   220â†’
   221â†’- **editable:** Allow editing the source code. Defaults to `false`.
   222â†’- **copyable:** Display the copy button on code snippets. Defaults to `true`.
   223â†’- **copy-js:** Copy JavaScript files for the editor to the output directory.
   224â†’  Defaults to `true`.
   225â†’- **line-numbers:** Display line numbers on editable sections of code. Requires both `editable` and `copy-js` to be `true`. Defaults to `false`.
   226â†’- **runnable:** Displays a run button for rust code snippets. Changing this to `false` will disable the run in playground feature globally. Defaults to `true`.
   227â†’
   228â†’[Ace]: https://ace.c9.io/
   229â†’
   230â†’### `[output.html.code]`
   231â†’
   232â†’The `[output.html.code]` table provides options for controlling code blocks.
   233â†’
   234â†’```toml
   235â†’[output.html.code]
   236â†’# A prefix string per language (one or more chars).
   237â†’# Any line starting with whitespace+prefix is hidden.
   238â†’hidelines = { python = "~" }
   239â†’```
   240â†’
   241â†’- **hidelines:** A table that defines how [hidden code lines](../mdbook.md#hiding-code-lines) work for each language.
   242â†’  The key is the language and the value is a string that will cause code lines starting with that prefix to be hidden.
   243â†’
   244â†’### `[output.html.search]`
   245â†’
   246â†’The `[output.html.search]` table provides options for controlling the built-in text [search].
   247â†’mdBook must be compiled with the `search` feature enabled (on by default).
   248â†’
   249â†’[search]: ../../guide/reading.md#search
   250â†’
   251â†’```toml
   252â†’[output.html.search]
   253â†’enable = true            # enables the search feature
   254â†’limit-results = 30       # maximum number of search results
   255â†’teaser-word-count = 30   # number of words used for a search result teaser
   256â†’use-boolean-and = true   # multiple search terms must all match
   257â†’boost-title = 2          # ranking boost factor for matches in headers
   258â†’boost-hierarchy = 1      # ranking boost factor for matches in page names
   259â†’boost-paragraph = 1      # ranking boost factor for matches in text
   260â†’expand = true            # partial words will match longer terms
   261â†’heading-split-level = 3  # link results to heading levels
   262â†’copy-js = true           # include Javascript code for search
   263â†’```
   264â†’
   265â†’- **enable:** Enables the search feature. Defaults to `true`.
   266â†’- **limit-results:** The maximum number of search results. Defaults to `30`.
   267â†’- **teaser-word-count:** The number of words used for a search result teaser.
   268â†’  Defaults to `30`.
   269â†’- **use-boolean-and:** Define the logical link between multiple search words. If
   270â†’  true, all search words must appear in each result. Defaults to `false`.
   271â†’- **boost-title:** Boost factor for the search result score if a search word
   272â†’  appears in the header. Defaults to `2`.
   273â†’- **boost-hierarchy:** Boost factor for the search result score if a search word
   274â†’  appears in the hierarchy. The hierarchy contains all titles of the parent
   275â†’  documents and all parent headings. Defaults to `1`.
   276â†’- **boost-paragraph:** Boost factor for the search result score if a search word
   277â†’  appears in the text. Defaults to `1`.
   278â†’- **expand:** True if search should match longer results e.g. search `micro`
   279â†’  should match `microwave`. Defaults to `true`.
   280â†’- **heading-split-level:** Search results will link to a section of the document
   281â†’  which contains the result. Documents are split into sections by headings this
   282â†’  level or less. Defaults to `3`. (`### This is a level 3 heading`)
   283â†’- **copy-js:** Copy JavaScript files for the search implementation to the output
   284â†’  directory. Defaults to `true`.
   285â†’
   286â†’#### `[output.html.search.chapter]`
   287â†’
   288â†’The [`output.html.search.chapter`] table provides the ability to modify search settings per chapter or directory. Each key is the path to the chapter source file or directory, and the value is a table of settings to apply to that path. This will merge recursively, with more specific paths taking precedence.
   289â†’
   290â†’```toml
   291â†’[output.html.search.chapter]
   292â†’# Disables search indexing for all chapters in the `appendix` directory.
   293â†’"appendix" = { enable = false }
   294â†’# Enables search indexing for just this one appendix chapter.
   295â†’"appendix/glossary.md" = { enable = true }
   296â†’```
   297â†’
   298â†’- **enable:** Enables or disables search indexing for the given chapters. Defaults to `true`. This does not override the overall `output.html.search.enable` setting; that must be `true` for any search functionality to be enabled. Be cautious when disabling indexing for chapters because that can potentially lead to user confusion when they search for terms and expect them to be found. This should only be used in exceptional circumstances where keeping the chapter in the index will cause issues with the quality of the search results.
   299â†’
   300â†’### `[output.html.redirect]`
   301â†’
   302â†’The `[output.html.redirect]` table provides a way to add redirects.
   303â†’This is useful when you move, rename, or remove a page to ensure that links to the old URL will go to the new location.
   304â†’
   305â†’```toml
   306â†’[output.html.redirect]
   307â†’"/appendices/bibliography.html" = "https://rustc-dev-guide.rust-lang.org/appendix/bibliography.html"
   308â†’"/other-installation-methods.html" = "../infra/other-installation-methods.html"
   309â†’
   310â†’# Fragment redirects also work.
   311â†’"/some-existing-page.html#old-fragment" = "some-existing-page.html#new-fragment"
   312â†’
   313â†’# Fragment redirects also work for deleted pages.
   314â†’"/old-page.html" = "new-page.html"
   315â†’"/old-page.html#old-fragment" = "new-page.html#new-fragment"
   316â†’```
   317â†’
   318â†’The table contains key-value pairs where the key is where the redirect file needs to be created, as an absolute path from the build directory, (e.g. `/appendices/bibliography.html`).
   319â†’The value can be any valid URI the browser should navigate to (e.g. `https://rust-lang.org/`, `/overview.html`, or `../bibliography.html`).
   320â†’
   321â†’This will generate an HTML page which will automatically redirect to the given location.
   322â†’
   323â†’When fragment redirects are specified, the page must use JavaScript to redirect to the correct location. This is useful if you rename or move a section header. Fragment redirects work with existing pages and deleted pages.
   324â†’
   325â†’## Markdown renderer
   326â†’
   327â†’The Markdown renderer will run preprocessors and then output the resulting
   328â†’Markdown. This is mostly useful for debugging preprocessors, especially in
   329â†’conjunction with `mdbook test` to see the Markdown that `mdbook` is passing
   330â†’to `rustdoc`.
   331â†’
   332â†’The Markdown renderer is included with `mdbook` but disabled by default.
   333â†’Enable it by adding an empty table to your `book.toml` as follows:
   334â†’
   335â†’```toml
   336â†’[output.markdown]
   337â†’```
   338â†’
   339â†’There are no configuration options for the Markdown renderer at this time;
   340â†’only whether it is enabled or disabled.
   341â†’
   342â†’See [the preprocessors documentation](preprocessors.md) for how to
   343â†’specify which preprocessors should run before the Markdown renderer.
format/example.rs
     1â†’fn main() {
     2â†’    println!("Hello World!");
     3â†’#
     4â†’#     // You can even hide lines! :D
     5â†’#     println!("I am hidden! Expand the code snippet to see me");
     6â†’}
format/markdown.md
     1â†’# Markdown
     2â†’
     3â†’mdBook's [parser](https://github.com/raphlinus/pulldown-cmark) adheres to the [CommonMark](https://commonmark.org/) specification with some extensions described below.
     4â†’You can take a quick [tutorial](https://commonmark.org/help/tutorial/),
     5â†’or [try out](https://spec.commonmark.org/dingus/) CommonMark in real time. A complete Markdown overview is out of scope for 
     6â†’this documentation, but below is a high level overview of some of the basics. For a more in-depth experience, check out the
     7â†’[Markdown Guide](https://www.markdownguide.org).
     8â†’
     9â†’## Text and paragraphs
    10â†’
    11â†’Text is rendered relatively predictably: 
    12â†’
    13â†’```markdown
    14â†’Here is a line of text.
    15â†’
    16â†’This is a new line.
    17â†’```
    18â†’
    19â†’Will look like you might expect:
    20â†’
    21â†’Here is a line of text.
    22â†’
    23â†’This is a new line.
    24â†’
    25â†’## Headings
    26â†’
    27â†’Headings use the `#` marker and should be on a line by themselves. More `#` mean smaller headings:
    28â†’
    29â†’```markdown
    30â†’### A heading 
    31â†’
    32â†’Some text.
    33â†’
    34â†’#### A smaller heading 
    35â†’
    36â†’More text.
    37â†’```
    38â†’
    39â†’### A heading 
    40â†’
    41â†’Some text.
    42â†’
    43â†’#### A smaller heading 
    44â†’
    45â†’More text.
    46â†’
    47â†’## Lists
    48â†’
    49â†’Lists can be unordered or ordered. Ordered lists will order automatically:
    50â†’
    51â†’```markdown
    52â†’* milk
    53â†’* eggs
    54â†’* butter
    55â†’
    56â†’1. carrots
    57â†’1. celery
    58â†’1. radishes
    59â†’```
    60â†’
    61â†’* milk
    62â†’* eggs
    63â†’* butter
    64â†’
    65â†’1. carrots
    66â†’1. celery
    67â†’1. radishes
    68â†’
    69â†’## Links
    70â†’
    71â†’Linking to a URL or local file is easy:
    72â†’
    73â†’```markdown
    74â†’Use [mdBook](https://github.com/rust-lang/mdBook). 
    75â†’
    76â†’Read about [mdBook](mdbook.md).
    77â†’
    78â†’And now [an mdBook link] that is not inline, unlike the above.
    79â†’
    80â†’A bare url: <https://www.rust-lang.org>.
    81â†’
    82â†’[an mdBook link]: https://github.com/rust-lang/mdBook
    83â†’```
    84â†’
    85â†’Use [mdBook](https://github.com/rust-lang/mdBook). 
    86â†’
    87â†’Read about [mdBook](mdbook.md).
    88â†’
    89â†’And now [an mdBook link] that is not inline, unlike the above.
    90â†’
    91â†’A bare url: <https://www.rust-lang.org>.
    92â†’
    93â†’[an mdBook link]: https://github.com/rust-lang/mdBook
    94â†’----
    95â†’
    96â†’Relative links that end with `.md` will be converted to the `.html` extension.
    97â†’It is recommended to use `.md` links when possible.
    98â†’This is useful when viewing the Markdown file outside of mdBook, for example on GitHub or GitLab which render Markdown automatically.
    99â†’
   100â†’Links to `README.md` will be converted to `index.html`.
   101â†’This is done since some services like GitHub render README files automatically, but web servers typically expect the root file to be called `index.html`.
   102â†’
   103â†’You can link to individual headings with `#` fragments.
   104â†’For example, `mdbook.md#text-and-paragraphs` would link to the [Text and Paragraphs](#text-and-paragraphs) section above.
   105â†’The ID is created by transforming the heading such as converting to lowercase and replacing spaces with dashes.
   106â†’You can click on any heading and look at the URL in your browser to see what the fragment looks like.
   107â†’
   108â†’## Images
   109â†’
   110â†’Including images is simply a matter of including a link to them, much like in the _Links_ section above. The following markdown
   111â†’includes the Rust logo SVG image found in the `images` directory at the same level as this file:
   112â†’
   113â†’```markdown
   114â†’![The Rust Logo](images/rust-logo-blk.svg)
   115â†’```
   116â†’
   117â†’Produces the following HTML when built with mdBook:
   118â†’
   119â†’```html
   120â†’<p><img src="images/rust-logo-blk.svg" alt="The Rust Logo" /></p>
   121â†’```
   122â†’
   123â†’Which, of course displays the image like so:
   124â†’
   125â†’![The Rust Logo](images/rust-logo-blk.svg)
   126â†’
   127â†’## Extensions
   128â†’
   129â†’mdBook has several extensions beyond the standard CommonMark specification.
   130â†’
   131â†’### Strikethrough
   132â†’
   133â†’Text may be rendered with a horizontal line through the center by wrapping the
   134â†’text with one or two tilde characters on each side:
   135â†’
   136â†’```text
   137â†’An example of ~~strikethrough text~~.
   138â†’```
   139â†’
   140â†’This example will render as:
   141â†’
   142â†’> An example of ~~strikethrough text~~.
   143â†’
   144â†’This follows the [GitHub Strikethrough extension][strikethrough].
   145â†’
   146â†’### Footnotes
   147â†’
   148â†’A footnote generates a small numbered link in the text which when clicked
   149â†’takes the reader to the footnote text at the bottom of the item. The footnote
   150â†’label is written similarly to a link reference with a caret at the front. The
   151â†’footnote text is written like a link reference definition, with the text
   152â†’following the label. Example:
   153â†’
   154â†’```text
   155â†’This is an example of a footnote[^note].
   156â†’
   157â†’[^note]: This text is the contents of the footnote, which will be rendered
   158â†’    towards the bottom.
   159â†’```
   160â†’
   161â†’This example will render as:
   162â†’
   163â†’> This is an example of a footnote[^note].
   164â†’>
   165â†’> [^note]: This text is the contents of the footnote, which will be rendered
   166â†’>     towards the bottom.
   167â†’
   168â†’The footnotes are automatically numbered based on the order the footnotes are
   169â†’written.
   170â†’
   171â†’### Tables
   172â†’
   173â†’Tables can be written using pipes and dashes to draw the rows and columns of
   174â†’the table. These will be translated to HTML table matching the shape. Example:
   175â†’
   176â†’```text
   177â†’| Header1 | Header2 |
   178â†’|---------|---------|
   179â†’| abc     | def     |
   180â†’```
   181â†’
   182â†’This example will render similarly to this:
   183â†’
   184â†’| Header1 | Header2 |
   185â†’|---------|---------|
   186â†’| abc     | def     |
   187â†’
   188â†’See the specification for the [GitHub Tables extension][tables] for more
   189â†’details on the exact syntax supported.
   190â†’
   191â†’### Task lists
   192â†’
   193â†’Task lists can be used as a checklist of items that have been completed.
   194â†’Example:
   195â†’
   196â†’```md
   197â†’- [x] Complete task
   198â†’- [ ] Incomplete task
   199â†’```
   200â†’
   201â†’This will render as:
   202â†’
   203â†’> - [x] Complete task
   204â†’> - [ ] Incomplete task
   205â†’
   206â†’See the specification for the [task list extension] for more details.
   207â†’
   208â†’### Smart punctuation
   209â†’
   210â†’Some ASCII punctuation sequences will be automatically turned into fancy Unicode
   211â†’characters:
   212â†’
   213â†’| ASCII sequence | Unicode |
   214â†’|----------------|---------|
   215â†’| `--`           | â€“       |
   216â†’| `---`          | â€”       |
   217â†’| `...`          | â€¦       |
   218â†’| `"`            | â€œ or â€‌, depending on context |
   219â†’| `'`            | â€ک or â€™, depending on context |
   220â†’
   221â†’So, no need to manually enter those Unicode characters!
   222â†’
   223â†’This feature is enabled by default.
   224â†’To disable it, see the [`output.html.smart-punctuation`] config option.
   225â†’
   226â†’[strikethrough]: https://github.github.com/gfm/#strikethrough-extension-
   227â†’[tables]: https://github.github.com/gfm/#tables-extension-
   228â†’[task list extension]: https://github.github.com/gfm/#task-list-items-extension-
   229â†’[`output.html.smart-punctuation`]: configuration/renderers.md#html-renderer-options
   230â†’
   231â†’### Heading attributes
   232â†’
   233â†’Headings can have a custom HTML ID and classes. This lets you maintain the same ID even if you change the heading's text, it also lets you add multiple classes in the heading.
   234â†’
   235â†’Example:
   236â†’```md
   237â†’# Example heading { #first .class1 .class2 }
   238â†’```
   239â†’
   240â†’This makes the level 1 heading with the content `Example heading`, ID `first`, and classes `class1` and `class2`. Note that the attributes should be space-separated.
   241â†’
   242â†’More information can be found in the [heading attrs spec page](https://github.com/raphlinus/pulldown-cmark/blob/master/pulldown-cmark/specs/heading_attrs.txt).
   243â†’
   244â†’### Definition lists
   245â†’
   246â†’Definition lists can be used for things like glossary entries. The term is listed on a line by itself, followed by one or more definitions. Each definition must begin with a `:` (after 0-2 spaces).
   247â†’
   248â†’Example:
   249â†’
   250â†’```md
   251â†’term A
   252â†’  : This is a definition of term A. Text
   253â†’    can span multiple lines.
   254â†’
   255â†’term B
   256â†’  : This is a definition of term B.
   257â†’  : This has more than one definition.
   258â†’```
   259â†’
   260â†’This will render as:
   261â†’
   262â†’term A
   263â†’  : This is a definition of term A. Text
   264â†’    can span multiple lines.
   265â†’
   266â†’term B
   267â†’  : This is a definition of term B.
   268â†’  : This has more than one definition.
   269â†’
   270â†’Terms are clickable just like headers, which will set the browser's URL to point directly to that term.
   271â†’
   272â†’See the [definition lists spec](https://github.com/pulldown-cmark/pulldown-cmark/blob/HEAD/pulldown-cmark/specs/definition_lists.txt) for more information on the specifics of the syntax. See the [Wikipedia guidelines for glossaries](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Manual_of_Style/Glossaries#General_guidelines_for_writing_glossaries) for some guidelines on how to write a glossary.
   273â†’
   274â†’This feature is enabled by default.
   275â†’To disable it, see the [`output.html.definition-lists`] config option.
   276â†’
   277â†’[`output.html.definition-lists`]: configuration/renderers.md#html-renderer-options
   278â†’
   279â†’### Admonitions
   280â†’
   281â†’An admonition is a special type of callout or notice block used to highlight important information. It is written as a blockquote with a special tag on the first line.
   282â†’
   283â†’```md
   284â†’> [!NOTE]
   285â†’> General information or additional context.
   286â†’
   287â†’> [!TIP]
   288â†’> A helpful suggestion or best practice.
   289â†’
   290â†’> [!IMPORTANT]
   291â†’> Key information that shouldn't be missed.
   292â†’
   293â†’> [!WARNING]
   294â†’> Critical information that highlights a potential risk.
   295â†’
   296â†’> [!CAUTION]
   297â†’> Information about potential issues that require caution.
   298â†’```
   299â†’
   300â†’These will render as:
   301â†’
   302â†’> [!NOTE]
   303â†’> General information or additional context.
   304â†’
   305â†’> [!TIP]
   306â†’> A helpful suggestion or best practice.
   307â†’
   308â†’> [!IMPORTANT]
   309â†’> Key information that shouldn't be missed.
   310â†’
   311â†’> [!WARNING]
   312â†’> Critical information that highlights a potential risk.
   313â†’
   314â†’> [!CAUTION]
   315â†’> Information about potential issues that require caution.
   316â†’
   317â†’This feature is enabled by default.
   318â†’To disable it, see the [`output.html.admonitions`] config option.
   319â†’
   320â†’[`output.html.admonitions`]: configuration/renderers.md#html-renderer-options
format/mathjax.md
     1â†’# MathJax support
     2â†’
     3â†’mdBook has optional support for math equations through
     4â†’[MathJax](https://www.mathjax.org/).
     5â†’
     6â†’To enable MathJax, you need to add the `mathjax-support` key to your `book.toml`
     7â†’under the `output.html` section.
     8â†’
     9â†’```toml
    10â†’[output.html]
    11â†’mathjax-support = true
    12â†’```
    13â†’
    14â†’>**Note:** The usual delimiters MathJax uses are not yet supported. You can't
    15â†’currently use `$$ ... $$` as delimiters and the `\[ ... \]` delimiters need an
    16â†’extra backslash to work. Hopefully this limitation will be lifted soon.
    17â†’
    18â†’>**Note:** When you use double backslashes in MathJax blocks (for example in
    19â†’> commands such as `\begin{cases} \frac 1 2 \\ \frac 3 4 \end{cases}`) you need
    20â†’> to add _two extra_ backslashes (e.g., `\begin{cases} \frac 1 2 \\\\ \frac 3 4
    21â†’> \end{cases}`).
    22â†’
    23â†’
    24â†’### Inline equations
    25â†’Inline equations are delimited by `\\(` and `\\)`. So for example, to render the
    26â†’following inline equation \\( \int x dx = \frac{x^2}{2} + C \\) you would write
    27â†’the following:
    28â†’```
    29â†’\\( \int x dx = \frac{x^2}{2} + C \\)
    30â†’```
    31â†’
    32â†’### Block equations
    33â†’Block equations are delimited by `\\[` and `\\]`. To render the following
    34â†’equation
    35â†’
    36â†’\\[ \mu = \frac{1}{N} \sum_{i=0} x_i \\]
    37â†’
    38â†’
    39â†’you would write:
    40â†’
    41â†’```bash
    42â†’\\[ \mu = \frac{1}{N} \sum_{i=0} x_i \\]
    43â†’```
format/mdbook.md
     1â†’# mdBook-specific features
     2â†’
     3â†’## Hiding code lines
     4â†’
     5â†’There is a feature in mdBook that lets you hide code lines by prepending them with a specific prefix.
     6â†’
     7â†’For the Rust language, you can prefix lines with `# ` (`#` followed by a space) to hide them [like you would with Rustdoc][rustdoc-hide].
     8â†’This prefix can be escaped with `##` to prevent the hiding of a line that should begin with the literal string `# ` (see [Rustdoc's docs][rustdoc-hide] for more details)
     9â†’
    10â†’[rustdoc-hide]: https://doc.rust-lang.org/stable/rustdoc/write-documentation/documentation-tests.html#hiding-portions-of-the-example
    11â†’
    12â†’```bash
    13â†’# fn main() {
    14â†’    let x = 5;
    15â†’    let y = 6;
    16â†’
    17â†’    println!("{}", x + y);
    18â†’# }
    19â†’```
    20â†’
    21â†’Will render as
    22â†’
    23â†’```rust
    24â†’# fn main() {
    25â†’    let x = 5;
    26â†’    let y = 6;
    27â†’
    28â†’    println!("{}", x + y);
    29â†’# }
    30â†’```
    31â†’
    32â†’When you tap or hover the mouse over the code block, there will be an eyeball icon (<i class="fa fa-eye"></i>) which will toggle the visibility of the hidden lines.
    33â†’
    34â†’By default, this only works for code examples that are annotated with `rust`.
    35â†’However, you can define custom prefixes for other languages by adding a new line-hiding prefix in your `book.toml` with the language name and prefix character(s):
    36â†’
    37â†’```toml
    38â†’[output.html.code.hidelines]
    39â†’python = "~"
    40â†’```
    41â†’
    42â†’The prefix will hide any lines that begin with the given prefix. With the python prefix shown above, this:
    43â†’
    44â†’```bash
    45â†’~hidden()
    46â†’nothidden():
    47â†’~    hidden()
    48â†’    ~hidden()
    49â†’    nothidden()
    50â†’```
    51â†’
    52â†’will render as
    53â†’
    54â†’```python
    55â†’~hidden()
    56â†’nothidden():
    57â†’~    hidden()
    58â†’    ~hidden()
    59â†’    nothidden()
    60â†’```
    61â†’
    62â†’This behavior can be overridden locally with a different prefix. This has the same effect as above:
    63â†’
    64â†’~~~markdown
    65â†’```python,hidelines=!!!
    66â†’!!!hidden()
    67â†’nothidden():
    68â†’!!!    hidden()
    69â†’    !!!hidden()
    70â†’    nothidden()
    71â†’```
    72â†’~~~
    73â†’
    74â†’## Rust playground
    75â†’
    76â†’Rust language code blocks will automatically get a play button (<i class="fas fa-play"></i>) which will execute the code and display the output just below the code block.
    77â†’This works by sending the code to the [Rust Playground].
    78â†’
    79â†’```rust
    80â†’println!("Hello, World!");
    81â†’```
    82â†’
    83â†’If there is no `main` function, then the code is automatically wrapped inside one.
    84â†’
    85â†’If you wish to disable the play button for a code block, you can include the `noplayground` option on the code block like this:
    86â†’
    87â†’~~~markdown
    88â†’```rust,noplayground
    89â†’let mut name = String::new();
    90â†’std::io::stdin().read_line(&mut name).expect("failed to read line");
    91â†’println!("Hello {}!", name);
    92â†’```
    93â†’~~~
    94â†’
    95â†’Or, if you wish to disable the play button for all code blocks in your book, you can write the config to the `book.toml` like this.
    96â†’
    97â†’```toml
    98â†’[output.html.playground]
    99â†’runnable = false
   100â†’```
   101â†’
   102â†’## Rust code block attributes
   103â†’
   104â†’Additional attributes can be included in Rust code blocks with comma, space, or tab-separated terms just after the language term. For example:
   105â†’
   106â†’~~~markdown
   107â†’```rust,ignore
   108â†’# This example won't be tested.
   109â†’panic!("oops!");
   110â†’```
   111â†’~~~
   112â†’
   113â†’These are particularly important when using [`mdbook test`] to test Rust examples.
   114â†’These use the same attributes as [rustdoc attributes], with a few additions:
   115â†’
   116â†’* `editable` --- Enables the [editor].
   117â†’* `noplayground` --- Removes the play button, but will still be tested.
   118â†’* `mdbook-runnable` --- Forces the play button to be displayed.
   119â†’  This is intended to be combined with the `ignore` attribute for examples that should not be tested, but you want to allow the reader to run.
   120â†’* `ignore` --- Will not be tested and no play button is shown, but it is still highlighted as Rust syntax.
   121â†’* `should_panic` --- When executed, it should produce a panic.
   122â†’* `no_run` --- The code is compiled when tested, but it is not run.
   123â†’  The play button is also not shown.
   124â†’* `compile_fail` --- The code should fail to compile.
   125â†’* `edition2015`, `edition2018`, `edition2021`, `edition2024` --- Forces the use of a specific Rust edition.
   126â†’  See [`rust.edition`] to set this globally.
   127â†’
   128â†’[`mdbook test`]: ../cli/test.md
   129â†’[rustdoc attributes]: https://doc.rust-lang.org/rustdoc/documentation-tests.html#attributes
   130â†’[editor]: theme/editor.md
   131â†’[`rust.edition`]: configuration/general.md#rust-options
   132â†’
   133â†’## Including files
   134â†’
   135â†’With the following syntax, you can include files into your book:
   136â†’
   137â†’```hbs
   138â†’\{{#include file.rs}}
   139â†’```
   140â†’
   141â†’The path to the file has to be relative from the current source file.
   142â†’
   143â†’mdBook will interpret included files as Markdown. Since the include command
   144â†’is usually used for inserting code snippets and examples, you will often
   145â†’wrap the command with ```` ``` ```` to display the file contents without
   146â†’interpreting them.
   147â†’
   148â†’````hbs
   149â†’```
   150â†’\{{#include file.rs}}
   151â†’```
   152â†’````
   153â†’
   154â†’## Including portions of a file
   155â†’Often you only need a specific part of the file, e.g. relevant lines for an
   156â†’example. We support four different modes of partial includes:
   157â†’
   158â†’```hbs
   159â†’\{{#include file.rs:2}}
   160â†’\{{#include file.rs::10}}
   161â†’\{{#include file.rs:2:}}
   162â†’\{{#include file.rs:2:10}}
   163â†’```
   164â†’
   165â†’The first command only includes the second line from file `file.rs`. The second
   166â†’command includes all lines up to line 10, i.e. the lines from 11 till the end of
   167â†’the file are omitted. The third command includes all lines from line 2, i.e. the
   168â†’first line is omitted. The last command includes the excerpt of `file.rs`
   169â†’consisting of lines 2 to 10.
   170â†’
   171â†’To avoid breaking your book when modifying included files, you can also
   172â†’include a specific section using anchors instead of line numbers.
   173â†’An anchor is a pair of matching lines. The line beginning an anchor must
   174â†’match the regex `ANCHOR:\s*[\w_-]+` and similarly the ending line must match
   175â†’the regex `ANCHOR_END:\s*[\w_-]+`. This allows you to put anchors in
   176â†’any kind of commented line.
   177â†’
   178â†’Consider the following file to include:
   179â†’```rs
   180â†’/* ANCHOR: all */
   181â†’
   182â†’// ANCHOR: component
   183â†’struct Paddle {
   184â†’    hello: f32,
   185â†’}
   186â†’// ANCHOR_END: component
   187â†’
   188â†’////////// ANCHOR: system
   189â†’impl System for MySystem { ... }
   190â†’////////// ANCHOR_END: system
   191â†’
   192â†’/* ANCHOR_END: all */
   193â†’```
   194â†’
   195â†’Then in the book, all you have to do is:
   196â†’````hbs
   197â†’Here is a component:
   198â†’```rust,no_run,noplayground
   199â†’\{{#include file.rs:component}}
   200â†’```
   201â†’
   202â†’Here is a system:
   203â†’```rust,no_run,noplayground
   204â†’\{{#include file.rs:system}}
   205â†’```
   206â†’
   207â†’This is the full file.
   208â†’```rust,no_run,noplayground
   209â†’\{{#include file.rs:all}}
   210â†’```
   211â†’````
   212â†’
   213â†’Lines containing anchor patterns inside the included anchor are ignored.
   214â†’
   215â†’## Including a file but initially hiding all except specified lines
   216â†’
   217â†’The `rustdoc_include` helper is for including code from external Rust files that contain complete
   218â†’examples, but only initially showing particular lines specified with line numbers or anchors in the
   219â†’same way as with `include`.
   220â†’
   221â†’The lines not in the line number range or between the anchors will still be included, but they will
   222â†’be prefaced with `#`. This way, a reader can expand the snippet to see the complete example, and
   223â†’Rustdoc will use the complete example when you run `mdbook test`.
   224â†’
   225â†’For example, consider a file named `file.rs` that contains this Rust program:
   226â†’
   227â†’```rust
   228â†’fn main() {
   229â†’    let x = add_one(2);
   230â†’    assert_eq!(x, 3);
   231â†’}
   232â†’
   233â†’fn add_one(num: i32) -> i32 {
   234â†’    num + 1
   235â†’}
   236â†’```
   237â†’
   238â†’We can include a snippet that initially shows only line 2 by using this syntax:
   239â†’
   240â†’````hbs
   241â†’To call the `add_one` function, we pass it an `i32` and bind the returned value to `x`:
   242â†’
   243â†’```rust
   244â†’\{{#rustdoc_include file.rs:2}}
   245â†’```
   246â†’````
   247â†’
   248â†’This would have the same effect as if we had manually inserted the code and hidden all but line 2
   249â†’using `#`:
   250â†’
   251â†’````hbs
   252â†’To call the `add_one` function, we pass it an `i32` and bind the returned value to `x`:
   253â†’
   254â†’```rust
   255â†’# fn main() {
   256â†’    let x = add_one(2);
   257â†’#     assert_eq!(x, 3);
   258â†’# }
   259â†’#
   260â†’# fn add_one(num: i32) -> i32 {
   261â†’#     num + 1
   262â†’# }
   263â†’```
   264â†’````
   265â†’
   266â†’That is, it looks like this (click the "expand" icon to see the rest of the file):
   267â†’
   268â†’```rust
   269â†’# fn main() {
   270â†’    let x = add_one(2);
   271â†’#     assert_eq!(x, 3);
   272â†’# }
   273â†’#
   274â†’# fn add_one(num: i32) -> i32 {
   275â†’#     num + 1
   276â†’# }
   277â†’```
   278â†’
   279â†’## Inserting runnable Rust files
   280â†’
   281â†’With the following syntax, you can insert runnable Rust files into your book:
   282â†’
   283â†’```hbs
   284â†’\{{#playground file.rs}}
   285â†’```
   286â†’
   287â†’The path to the Rust file has to be relative from the current source file.
   288â†’
   289â†’When play is clicked, the code snippet will be sent to the [Rust Playground] to be
   290â†’compiled and run. The result is sent back and displayed directly underneath the
   291â†’code.
   292â†’
   293â†’Here is what a rendered code snippet looks like:
   294â†’
   295â†’{{#playground example.rs}}
   296â†’
   297â†’Any additional values passed after the filename will be included as attributes of the code block.
   298â†’For example `\{{#playground example.rs editable}}` will create the code block like the following:
   299â†’
   300â†’~~~markdown
   301â†’```rust,editable
   302â†’# Contents of example.rs here.
   303â†’```
   304â†’~~~
   305â†’
   306â†’And the `editable` attribute will enable the [editor] as described at [Rust code block attributes](#rust-code-block-attributes).
   307â†’
   308â†’[Rust Playground]: https://play.rust-lang.org/
   309â†’
   310â†’## Controlling page \<title\>
   311â†’
   312â†’A chapter can set a \<title\> that is different from its entry in the table of
   313â†’contents (sidebar) by including a `\{{#title ...}}` near the top of the page.
   314â†’
   315â†’```hbs
   316â†’\{{#title My Title}}
   317â†’```
   318â†’
   319â†’## HTML classes provided by mdBook
   320â†’
   321â†’<img class="right" src="images/rust-logo-blk.svg" alt="The Rust logo">
   322â†’
   323â†’### `class="left"` and `"right"`
   324â†’
   325â†’These classes are provided by default, for inline HTML to float images.
   326â†’
   327â†’```html
   328â†’<img class="right" src="images/rust-logo-blk.svg" alt="The Rust logo">
   329â†’```
   330â†’
   331â†’### `class="hidden"`
   332â†’
   333â†’HTML tags with class `hidden` will not be shown.
   334â†’
   335â†’```html
   336â†’<div class="hidden">This will not be seen.</div>
   337â†’```
   338â†’
   339â†’<div class="hidden">This will not be seen.</div>
   340â†’
   341â†’## Font-Awesome icons
   342â†’
   343â†’mdBook includes a copy of version 6 of [Font Awesome Free's](https://fontawesome.com)
   344â†’MIT-licensed SVG files. It emulates the `<i>` syntax, but converts the results
   345â†’to inline SVG. Only the regular, solid, and brands icons are included; paid
   346â†’features like the light icons are not.
   347â†’
   348â†’For example, given this HTML syntax:
   349â†’
   350â†’```hbs
   351â†’The result looks like this: <i class="fa-solid fa-print"></i>
   352â†’```
   353â†’
   354â†’The result looks like this: <i class="fa-solid fa-print"></i>
   355â†’
   356â†’See the [free icon set](https://fontawesome.com/v6/search) for the available icons.
format/summary.md
     1â†’# SUMMARY.md
     2â†’
     3â†’The summary file is used by mdBook to know what chapters to include, in what
     4â†’order they should appear, what their hierarchy is and where the source files
     5â†’are. Without this file, there is no book.
     6â†’
     7â†’This markdown file must be named `SUMMARY.md`. Its formatting
     8â†’is very strict and must follow the structure outlined below to allow for easy
     9â†’parsing. Any element not specified below, be it formatting or textual, is likely
    10â†’to be ignored at best, or may cause an error when attempting to build the book.
    11â†’
    12â†’### Structure
    13â†’
    14â†’1. ***Title*** - While optional, it's common practice to begin with a title, generally <code
    15â†’   class="language-markdown"># Summary</code>. This is ignored by the parser however, and
    16â†’   can be omitted.
    17â†’   ```markdown
    18â†’   # Summary
    19â†’   ```
    20â†’
    21â†’1. ***Prefix Chapter*** - Before the main numbered chapters, prefix chapters can be added
    22â†’   that will not be numbered. This is useful for forewords,
    23â†’   introductions, etc. There are, however, some constraints. Prefix chapters cannot be
    24â†’   nested; they should all be on the root level. And you cannot add
    25â†’   prefix chapters once you have added numbered chapters.
    26â†’   ```markdown
    27â†’   [A Prefix Chapter](relative/path/to/markdown.md)
    28â†’
    29â†’   - [First Chapter](relative/path/to/markdown2.md)
    30â†’   ```
    31â†’
    32â†’1. ***Part Title*** -
    33â†’   Level 1 headers can be used as a title for the following numbered chapters.
    34â†’   This can be used to logically separate different sections of the book.
    35â†’   The title is rendered as unclickable text.
    36â†’   Titles are optional, and the numbered chapters can be broken into as many parts as desired.
    37â†’   Part titles must be h1 headers (one `#`), other heading levels are ignored.
    38â†’   ```markdown
    39â†’   # My Part Title
    40â†’
    41â†’   - [First Chapter](relative/path/to/markdown.md)
    42â†’   ```
    43â†’
    44â†’1. ***Numbered Chapter*** - Numbered chapters outline the main content of the book
    45â†’   and can be nested, resulting in a nice hierarchy
    46â†’   (chapters, sub-chapters, etc.).
    47â†’   ```markdown
    48â†’   # Title of Part
    49â†’
    50â†’   - [First Chapter](relative/path/to/markdown.md)
    51â†’   - [Second Chapter](relative/path/to/markdown2.md)
    52â†’      - [Sub Chapter](relative/path/to/markdown3.md)
    53â†’
    54â†’   # Title of Another Part
    55â†’
    56â†’   - [Another Chapter](relative/path/to/markdown4.md)
    57â†’   ```
    58â†’   Numbered chapters can be denoted with either `-` or `*` (do not mix delimiters). 
    59â†’   
    60â†’1. ***Suffix Chapter*** - Like prefix chapters, suffix chapters are unnumbered, but they come after 
    61â†’   numbered chapters.
    62â†’   ```markdown
    63â†’   - [Last Chapter](relative/path/to/markdown.md)
    64â†’
    65â†’   [Title of Suffix Chapter](relative/path/to/markdown2.md)
    66â†’   ```
    67â†’
    68â†’1. ***Draft chapters*** - Draft chapters are chapters without a file and thus content.
    69â†’   The purpose of a draft chapter is to signal future chapters still to be written.
    70â†’   Or when still laying out the structure of the book to avoid creating the files
    71â†’   while you are still changing the structure of the book a lot.
    72â†’   Draft chapters will be rendered in the HTML renderer as disabled links in the table
    73â†’   of contents, as you can see for the next chapter in the table of contents on the left.
    74â†’   Draft chapters are written like normal chapters but without writing the path to the file.
    75â†’   ```markdown
    76â†’   - [Draft Chapter]()
    77â†’   ```
    78â†’
    79â†’1. ***Separators*** - Separators can be added before, in between, and after any other element. They result
    80â†’   in an HTML rendered line in the built table of contents.  A separator is
    81â†’   a line containing exclusively dashes and at least three of them: `---`.
    82â†’   ```markdown
    83â†’   # My Part Title
    84â†’   
    85â†’   [A Prefix Chapter](relative/path/to/markdown.md)
    86â†’
    87â†’   ---
    88â†’
    89â†’   - [First Chapter](relative/path/to/markdown2.md)
    90â†’   ```
    91â†’  
    92â†’
    93â†’### Example
    94â†’
    95â†’Below is the markdown source for the `SUMMARY.md` for this guide, with the resulting table
    96â†’of contents as rendered to the left.
    97â†’
    98â†’```markdown
    99â†’{{#include ../SUMMARY.md}}
   100â†’```
format/theme/README.md
     1â†’# Theme
     2â†’
     3â†’The default renderer uses a [handlebars](https://handlebarsjs.com) template to
     4â†’render your markdown files and comes with a default theme included in the mdBook
     5â†’binary.
     6â†’
     7â†’The theme is totally customizable, you can selectively replace every file from
     8â†’the theme by your own by adding a `theme` directory next to `src` folder in your
     9â†’project root. Create a new file with the name of the file you want to override
    10â†’and now that file will be used instead of the default file.
    11â†’
    12â†’Here are the files you can override:
    13â†’
    14â†’- **_index.hbs_** is the handlebars template.
    15â†’- **_head.hbs_** is appended to the HTML `<head>` section.
    16â†’- **_header.hbs_** content is appended on top of every book page.
    17â†’- **_css/_** contains the CSS files for styling the book.
    18â†’    - **_css/chrome.css_** is for UI elements.
    19â†’    - **_css/general.css_** is the base styles.
    20â†’    - **_css/print.css_** is the style for printer output.
    21â†’    - **_css/variables.css_** contains variables used in other CSS files.
    22â†’- **_book.js_** is mostly used to add client side functionality, like hiding /
    23â†’  un-hiding the sidebar, changing the theme, ...
    24â†’- **_highlight.js_** is the JavaScript that is used to highlight code snippets,
    25â†’  you should not need to modify this.
    26â†’- **_highlight.css_** is the theme used for the code highlighting.
    27â†’- **_favicon.svg_** and **_favicon.png_** the favicon that will be used. The SVG
    28â†’  version is used by [newer browsers].
    29â†’- **fonts/fonts.css** contains the definition of which fonts to load.
    30â†’  Custom fonts can be included in the `fonts` directory.
    31â†’
    32â†’Generally, when you want to tweak the theme, you don't need to override all the
    33â†’files. If you only need changes in the stylesheet, there is no point in
    34â†’overriding all the other files. Because custom files take precedence over
    35â†’built-in ones, they will not get updated with new fixes / features.
    36â†’
    37â†’**Note:** When you override a file, it is possible that you break some
    38â†’functionality. Therefore I recommend to use the file from the default theme as
    39â†’template and only add / modify what you need. You can copy the default theme
    40â†’into your source directory automatically by using `mdbook init --theme` and just
    41â†’remove the files you don't want to override.
    42â†’
    43â†’`mdbook init --theme` will not create every file listed above.
    44â†’Some files, such as `head.hbs`, do not have built-in equivalents.
    45â†’Just create the file if you need it.
    46â†’
    47â†’If you completely replace all built-in themes, be sure to also set
    48â†’[`output.html.preferred-dark-theme`] in the config, which defaults to the
    49â†’built-in `navy` theme.
    50â†’
    51â†’[`output.html.preferred-dark-theme`]: ../configuration/renderers.md#html-renderer-options
    52â†’[newer browsers]: https://caniuse.com/#feat=link-icon-svg
format/theme/editor.md
     1â†’# Editor
     2â†’
     3â†’In addition to providing runnable code playgrounds, mdBook optionally allows them
     4â†’to be editable. In order to enable editable code blocks, the following needs to
     5â†’be added to the ***book.toml***:
     6â†’
     7â†’```toml
     8â†’[output.html.playground]
     9â†’editable = true
    10â†’```
    11â†’
    12â†’After enabling editable code blocks, the `editable` attribute must be added to a
    13â†’code block to make it editable:
    14â†’
    15â†’~~~markdown
    16â†’```rust,editable
    17â†’fn main() {
    18â†’    let number = 5;
    19â†’    print!("{}", number);
    20â†’}
    21â†’```
    22â†’~~~
    23â†’
    24â†’The above will result in this editable playground:
    25â†’
    26â†’```rust,editable
    27â†’fn main() {
    28â†’    let number = 5;
    29â†’    print!("{}", number);
    30â†’}
    31â†’```
    32â†’
    33â†’Note the new `Undo Changes` button in the editable playgrounds.
    34â†’
    35â†’## Customizing the editor
    36â†’
    37â†’By default, the editor is the [Ace](https://ace.c9.io/) editor, but, if desired,
    38â†’the functionality may be overridden by providing a different folder:
    39â†’
    40â†’```toml
    41â†’[output.html.playground]
    42â†’editable = true
    43â†’editor = "/path/to/editor"
    44â†’```
    45â†’
    46â†’Note that for the editor changes to function correctly, the `book.js` inside of
    47â†’the `theme` folder will need to be overridden as it has some couplings with the
    48â†’default Ace editor.
format/theme/index-hbs.md
     1â†’# index.hbs
     2â†’
     3â†’`index.hbs` is the handlebars template that is used to render the book. The
     4â†’markdown files are processed to html and then injected in that template.
     5â†’
     6â†’If you want to change the layout or style of your book, chances are that you
     7â†’will have to modify this template a little bit. Here is what you need to know.
     8â†’
     9â†’## Data
    10â†’
    11â†’A lot of data is exposed to the handlebars template with the "context". In the
    12â†’handlebars template you can access this information by using
    13â†’
    14â†’```handlebars
    15â†’{{name_of_property}}
    16â†’```
    17â†’
    18â†’Here is a list of the properties that are exposed:
    19â†’
    20â†’- ***language*** Language of the book in the form `en`, as specified in `book.toml` (if not specified, defaults to `en`). To use in <code
    21â†’  class="language-html">\<html lang=\"{{ language }}\"></code> for example.
    22â†’- ***title*** Title used for the current page. This is identical to `{{ chapter_title }} - {{ book_title }}` unless `book_title` is not set in which case it just defaults to the `chapter_title`.
    23â†’- ***book_title*** Title of the book, as specified in `book.toml`
    24â†’- ***chapter_title*** Title of the current chapter, as listed in `SUMMARY.md`
    25â†’
    26â†’- ***path*** Relative path to the original markdown file from the source
    27â†’  directory
    28â†’- ***content*** This is the rendered markdown.
    29â†’- ***path_to_root*** This is a path containing exclusively `../`'s that points
    30â†’  to the root of the book from the current file. Since the original directory
    31â†’  structure is maintained, it is useful to prepend relative links with this
    32â†’  `path_to_root`.
    33â†’- ***previous*** and ***next*** These are objects used for linking to the previous and next chapter. They contain the properties `title` and `link` of the corresponding chapter.
    34â†’- ***chapters*** Is an array of dictionaries of the form
    35â†’  ```json
    36â†’  {"section": "1.2.1", "name": "name of this chapter", "path": "dir/markdown.md"}
    37â†’  ```
    38â†’  containing all the chapters of the book. It is used for example to construct
    39â†’  the table of contents (sidebar).
    40â†’
    41â†’## Handlebars helpers
    42â†’
    43â†’In addition to the properties you can access, there are some handlebars helpers
    44â†’at your disposal.
    45â†’
    46â†’### toc
    47â†’
    48â†’The toc helper is used like this
    49â†’
    50â†’```handlebars
    51â†’{{#toc}}{{/toc}}
    52â†’```
    53â†’
    54â†’and outputs something that looks like this, depending on the structure of your
    55â†’book
    56â†’
    57â†’```html
    58â†’<ul class="chapter">
    59â†’    <li><a href="link/to/file.html">Some chapter</a></li>
    60â†’    <li>
    61â†’        <ul class="section">
    62â†’            <li><a href="link/to/other_file.html">Some other Chapter</a></li>
    63â†’        </ul>
    64â†’    </li>
    65â†’</ul>
    66â†’```
    67â†’
    68â†’If you would like to make a toc with another structure, you have access to the
    69â†’chapters property containing all the data. The only limitation at the moment
    70â†’is that you would have to do it with JavaScript instead of with a handlebars
    71â†’helper.
    72â†’
    73â†’```html
    74â†’<script>
    75â†’var chapters = {{chapters}};
    76â†’// Processing here
    77â†’</script>
    78â†’```
    79â†’
    80â†’### resource
    81â†’
    82â†’The path to a static file.
    83â†’It implicitly includes `path_to_root`,
    84â†’and accounts for files that are renamed with a hash in their filename.
    85â†’
    86â†’```handlebars
    87â†’<link rel="stylesheet" href="{{ resource "css/chrome.css" }}">
    88â†’```
    89â†’
    90â†’### fa
    91â†’
    92â†’mdBook includes a copy of [Font Awesome Free's](https://fontawesome.com)
    93â†’MIT-licensed SVG files. It accepts three positional arguments:
    94â†’
    95â†’1. Type: one of "solid", "regular", and "brands" (light and duotone are not
    96â†’   currently supported)
    97â†’2. Icon: anything chosen from the
    98â†’   [free icon set](https://fontawesome.com/v6/search)
    99â†’3. ID (optional): if included, an HTML ID attribute will be added to the
   100â†’   icon's wrapping `<span>` tag
   101â†’
   102â†’For example, this handlebars syntax will become this HTML:
   103â†’
   104â†’```handlebars
   105â†’{{fa "solid" "print" "print-button"}}
   106â†’```
   107â†’
   108â†’```html
   109â†’<span class=fa-svg id="print-button"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" viewBox="0 0 512 512"><path d="M448 192V77.25c0-8.49-3.37-16.62-9.37-22.63L393.37 9.37c-6-6-14.14-9.37-22.63-9.37H96C78.33 0 64 14.33 64 32v160c-35.35 0-64 28.65-64 64v112c0 8.84 7.16 16 16 16h48v96c0 17.67 14.33 32 32 32h320c17.67 0 32-14.33 32-32v-96h48c8.84 0 16-7.16 16-16V256c0-35.35-28.65-64-64-64zm-64 256H128v-96h256v96zm0-224H128V64h192v48c0 8.84 7.16 16 16 16h48v96zm48 72c-13.25 0-24-10.75-24-24 0-13.26 10.75-24 24-24s24 10.74 24 24c0 13.25-10.75 24-24 24z"/></svg></span>
   110â†’```
format/theme/syntax-highlighting.md
     1â†’# Syntax highlighting
     2â†’
     3â†’mdBook uses [Highlight.js](https://highlightjs.org) with a custom theme
     4â†’for syntax highlighting.
     5â†’
     6â†’Automatic language detection has been turned off, so you will probably want to
     7â†’specify the programming language you use like this:
     8â†’
     9â†’~~~markdown
    10â†’```rust
    11â†’fn main() {
    12â†’    // Some code
    13â†’}
    14â†’```
    15â†’~~~
    16â†’
    17â†’## Supported languages
    18â†’
    19â†’These languages are supported by default, but you can add more by supplying
    20â†’your own `highlight.js` file:
    21â†’
    22â†’- apache
    23â†’- armasm
    24â†’- bash
    25â†’- c
    26â†’- coffeescript
    27â†’- cpp
    28â†’- csharp
    29â†’- css
    30â†’- d
    31â†’- diff
    32â†’- go
    33â†’- handlebars
    34â†’- haskell
    35â†’- http
    36â†’- ini
    37â†’- java
    38â†’- javascript
    39â†’- json
    40â†’- julia
    41â†’- kotlin
    42â†’- less
    43â†’- lua
    44â†’- makefile
    45â†’- markdown
    46â†’- nginx
    47â†’- nim
    48â†’- nix
    49â†’- objectivec
    50â†’- perl
    51â†’- php
    52â†’- plaintext
    53â†’- properties
    54â†’- python
    55â†’- r
    56â†’- ruby
    57â†’- rust
    58â†’- scala
    59â†’- scss
    60â†’- shell
    61â†’- sql
    62â†’- swift
    63â†’- typescript
    64â†’- x86asm
    65â†’- xml
    66â†’- yaml
    67â†’
    68â†’## Custom theme
    69â†’Like the rest of the theme, the files used for syntax highlighting can be
    70â†’overridden with your own.
    71â†’
    72â†’- ***highlight.js*** normally you shouldn't have to overwrite this file, unless
    73â†’  you want to use a more recent version.
    74â†’- ***highlight.css*** theme used by highlight.js for syntax highlighting.
    75â†’
    76â†’If you want to use another theme for `highlight.js` download it from their
    77â†’website, or make it yourself, rename it to `highlight.css` and put it in
    78â†’the `theme` folder of your book.
    79â†’
    80â†’Now your theme will be used instead of the default theme.
    81â†’
    82â†’## Improve default theme
    83â†’
    84â†’If you think the default theme doesn't look quite right for a specific language,
    85â†’or could be improved, feel free to [submit a new
    86â†’issue](https://github.com/rust-lang/mdBook/issues) explaining what you
    87â†’have in mind and I will take a look at it.
    88â†’
    89â†’You could also create a pull-request with the proposed improvements.
    90â†’
    91â†’Overall the theme should be light and sober, without too many flashy colors.
guide/README.md
     1â†’# User guide
     2â†’
     3â†’This user guide provides an introduction to basic concepts of using mdBook.
     4â†’
     5â†’- [Installation](installation.md)
     6â†’- [Reading Books](reading.md)
     7â†’- [Creating a Book](creating.md)
guide/creating.md
     1â†’# Creating a book
     2â†’
     3â†’Once you have the `mdbook` CLI tool installed, you can use it to create and render a book.
     4â†’
     5â†’## Initializing a book
     6â†’
     7â†’The `mdbook init` command will create a new directory containing an empty book for you to get started.
     8â†’Give it the name of the directory that you want to create:
     9â†’
    10â†’```sh
    11â†’mdbook init my-first-book
    12â†’```
    13â†’
    14â†’It will ask a few questions before generating the book.
    15â†’After answering the questions, you can change the current directory into the new book:
    16â†’
    17â†’```sh
    18â†’cd my-first-book
    19â†’```
    20â†’
    21â†’There are several ways to render a book, but one of the easiest methods is to use the `serve` command, which will build your book and start a local webserver:
    22â†’
    23â†’```sh
    24â†’mdbook serve --open
    25â†’```
    26â†’
    27â†’The `--open` option will open your default web browser to view your new book.
    28â†’You can leave the server running even while you edit the content of the book, and `mdbook` will automatically rebuild the output *and* automatically refresh your web browser.
    29â†’
    30â†’Check out the [CLI Guide](../cli/index.html) for more information about other `mdbook` commands and CLI options.
    31â†’
    32â†’## Anatomy of a book
    33â†’
    34â†’A book is built from several files which define the settings and layout of the book.
    35â†’
    36â†’### `book.toml`
    37â†’
    38â†’In the root of your book, there is a `book.toml` file which contains settings for describing how to build your book.
    39â†’This is written in the [TOML markup language](https://toml.io/).
    40â†’The default settings are usually good enough to get you started.
    41â†’When you are interested in exploring more features and options that mdBook provides, check out the [Configuration chapter](../format/configuration/index.html) for more details.
    42â†’
    43â†’A very basic `book.toml` can be as simple as this:
    44â†’
    45â†’```toml
    46â†’[book]
    47â†’title = "My First Book"
    48â†’```
    49â†’
    50â†’### `SUMMARY.md`
    51â†’
    52â†’The next major part of a book is the summary file located at `src/SUMMARY.md`.
    53â†’This file contains a list of all the chapters in the book.
    54â†’Before a chapter can be viewed, it must be added to this list.
    55â†’
    56â†’Here's a basic summary file with a few chapters:
    57â†’
    58â†’```md
    59â†’# Summary
    60â†’
    61â†’[Introduction](README.md)
    62â†’
    63â†’- [My First Chapter](my-first-chapter.md)
    64â†’- [Nested example](nested/README.md)
    65â†’    - [Sub-chapter](nested/sub-chapter.md)
    66â†’```
    67â†’
    68â†’Try opening up `src/SUMMARY.md` in your editor and adding a few chapters.
    69â†’If any of the chapter files do not exist, `mdbook` will automatically create them for you.
    70â†’
    71â†’For more details on other formatting options for the summary file, check out the [Summary chapter](../format/summary.md).
    72â†’
    73â†’### Source files
    74â†’
    75â†’The content of your book is all contained in the `src` directory.
    76â†’Each chapter is a separate Markdown file.
    77â†’Typically, each chapter starts with a level 1 heading with the title of the chapter.
    78â†’
    79â†’```md
    80â†’# My First Chapter
    81â†’
    82â†’Fill out your content here.
    83â†’```
    84â†’
    85â†’The precise layout of the files is up to you.
    86â†’The organization of the files will correspond to the HTML files generated, so keep in mind that the file layout is part of the URL of each chapter.
    87â†’
    88â†’While the `mdbook serve` command is running, you can open any of the chapter files and start editing them.
    89â†’Each time you save the file, `mdbook` will rebuild the book and refresh your web browser.
    90â†’
    91â†’Check out the [Markdown chapter](../format/markdown.md) for more information on formatting the content of your chapters.
    92â†’
    93â†’All other files in the `src` directory will be included in the output.
    94â†’So if you have images or other static files, just include them somewhere in the `src` directory.
    95â†’
    96â†’## Publishing a book
    97â†’
    98â†’Once you've written your book, you may want to host it somewhere for others to view.
    99â†’The first step is to build the output of the book.
   100â†’This can be done with the `mdbook build` command in the same directory where the `book.toml` file is located:
   101â†’
   102â†’```sh
   103â†’mdbook build
   104â†’```
   105â†’
   106â†’This will generate a directory named `book` which contains the HTML content of your book.
   107â†’You can then place this directory on any web server to host it.
   108â†’
   109â†’For more information about publishing and deploying, check out the [Continuous Integration chapter](../continuous-integration.md) for more.
guide/installation.md
     1â†’# Installation
     2â†’
     3â†’There are multiple ways to install the mdBook CLI tool.
     4â†’Choose any one of the methods below that best suit your needs.
     5â†’If you are installing mdBook for automatic deployment, check out the [continuous integration] chapter for more examples on how to install.
     6â†’
     7â†’[continuous integration]: ../continuous-integration.md
     8â†’
     9â†’## Pre-compiled binaries
    10â†’
    11â†’Executable binaries are available for download on the [GitHub Releases page][releases].
    12â†’Download the binary for your platform (Windows, macOS, or Linux) and extract the archive.
    13â†’The archive contains an `mdbook` executable which you can run to build your books.
    14â†’
    15â†’To make it easier to run, put the path to the binary into your `PATH`.
    16â†’
    17â†’[releases]: https://github.com/rust-lang/mdBook/releases
    18â†’
    19â†’## Build from source using Rust
    20â†’
    21â†’To build the `mdbook` executable from source, you will first need to install Rust and Cargo.
    22â†’Follow the instructions on the [Rust installation page].
    23â†’mdBook currently requires at least Rust version 1.88.
    24â†’
    25â†’Once you have installed Rust, the following command can be used to build and install mdBook:
    26â†’
    27â†’```sh
    28â†’cargo install mdbook
    29â†’```
    30â†’
    31â†’This will automatically download mdBook from [crates.io], build it, and install it in Cargo's global binary directory (`~/.cargo/bin/` by default).
    32â†’
    33â†’You can run `cargo install mdbook` again whenever you want to update to a new version.
    34â†’That command will check if there is a newer version, and re-install mdBook if a newer version is found.
    35â†’
    36â†’To uninstall, run the command `cargo uninstall mdbook`.
    37â†’
    38â†’[Rust installation page]: https://www.rust-lang.org/tools/install
    39â†’[crates.io]: https://crates.io/
    40â†’
    41â†’### Installing the latest master version
    42â†’
    43â†’The version published to crates.io will ever so slightly be behind the version hosted on GitHub.
    44â†’If you need the latest version you can build the git version of mdBook yourself.
    45â†’Cargo makes this ***super easy***!
    46â†’
    47â†’```sh
    48â†’cargo install --git https://github.com/rust-lang/mdBook.git mdbook
    49â†’```
    50â†’
    51â†’Again, make sure to add the Cargo bin directory to your `PATH`.
    52â†’
    53â†’## Modifying and contributing
    54â†’
    55â†’If you are interested in making modifications to mdBook itself, check out the [Contributing Guide] for more information.
    56â†’
    57â†’[Contributing Guide]: https://github.com/rust-lang/mdBook/blob/master/CONTRIBUTING.md
guide/reading.md
     1â†’# Reading books
     2â†’
     3â†’This chapter gives an introduction on how to interact with a book produced by mdBook.
     4â†’This assumes you are reading an HTML book.
     5â†’The options and formatting will be different for other output formats such as PDF.
     6â†’
     7â†’A book is organized into *chapters*.
     8â†’Each chapter is a separate page.
     9â†’Chapters can be nested into a hierarchy of sub-chapters.
    10â†’Typically, each chapter will be organized into a series of *headings* to subdivide a chapter.
    11â†’
    12â†’## Navigation
    13â†’
    14â†’There are several methods for navigating through the chapters of a book.
    15â†’
    16â†’The **sidebar** on the left provides a list of all chapters.
    17â†’Clicking on any of the chapter titles will load that page.
    18â†’
    19â†’The sidebar may not automatically appear if the window is too narrow, particularly on mobile displays.
    20â†’In that situation, the menu icon (three horizontal bars) at the top-left of the page can be pressed to open and close the sidebar.
    21â†’
    22â†’The **arrow buttons** at the bottom of the page can be used to navigate to the previous or the next chapter.
    23â†’
    24â†’The **left and right arrow keys** on the keyboard can be used to navigate to the previous or the next chapter.
    25â†’
    26â†’## Top menu bar
    27â†’
    28â†’The menu bar at the top of the page provides some icons for interacting with the book.
    29â†’The icons displayed will depend on the settings of how the book was generated.
    30â†’
    31â†’| Icon | Description |
    32â†’|------|-------------|
    33â†’| <i class="fas fa-bars"></i> | Opens and closes the chapter listing sidebar. |
    34â†’| <i class="fas fa-paintbrush"></i> | Opens a picker to choose a different color theme. |
    35â†’| <i class="fas fa-magnifying-glass"></i> | Opens a search bar for searching within the book. |
    36â†’| <i class="fas fa-print"></i> | Instructs the web browser to print the entire book. |
    37â†’| <i class="fab fa-github"></i> | Opens a link to the website that hosts the source code of the book. |
    38â†’| <i class="fas fa-pencil"></i> | Opens a page to directly edit the source of the page you are currently reading. |
    39â†’
    40â†’Tapping the menu bar will scroll the page to the top.
    41â†’
    42â†’## Search
    43â†’
    44â†’Each book has a built-in search system.
    45â†’Pressing the search icon <i class="fas fa-magnifying-glass"></i> in the menu bar, or pressing the <kbd>/</kbd> or <kbd>S</kbd> key on the keyboard will open an input box for entering search terms.
    46â†’Typing some terms will show matching chapters and sections in real time.
    47â†’
    48â†’Clicking any of the results will jump to that section.
    49â†’The up and down arrow keys can be used to navigate the results, and enter will open the highlighted section.
    50â†’
    51â†’After loading a search result, the matching search terms will be highlighted in the text.
    52â†’Clicking a highlighted word or pressing the <kbd>Escape</kbd> key will remove the highlighting.
    53â†’
    54â†’## Code blocks
    55â†’
    56â†’mdBook books are often used for programming projects, and thus support highlighting code blocks and samples.
    57â†’Code blocks may contain several different icons for interacting with them:
    58â†’
    59â†’| Icon | Description |
    60â†’|------|-------------|
    61â†’| <i class="fa fa-copy"></i> | Copies the code block into your local clipboard, to allow pasting into another application. |
    62â†’| <i class="fas fa-play"></i> | For Rust code examples, this will execute the sample code and display the compiler output just below the example (see [playground]). |
    63â†’| <i class="fa fa-eye"></i> | For Rust code examples, this will toggle visibility of "hidden" lines. Sometimes, larger examples will hide lines which are not particularly relevant to what is being illustrated (see [hiding code lines]). |
    64â†’| <i class="fas fa-clock-rotate-left"></i> | For [editable code examples][editor], this will undo any changes you have made. |
    65â†’
    66â†’Here's an example:
    67â†’
    68â†’```rust
    69â†’println!("Hello, World!");
    70â†’```
    71â†’
    72â†’[editor]: ../format/theme/editor.md
    73â†’[playground]: ../format/mdbook.md#rust-playground
    74â†’[hiding code lines]: ../format/mdbook.md#hiding-code-lines
